# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: climate-change
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The **2019–20 Australian bushfire season**, also known as the **Black Summer**, was one of the most intense and catastrophic fire seasons on record in Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Exceptionally dry conditions, a lack of soil moisture, and early fires in Central Queensland led to a premature start to the bushfire season from June 2019.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over ten thousand fires burnt, mainly in the south-east of the country, until March 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The most severe fires hit from December 2019 to January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires burnt more than 24 million hectares (59 million acres; 240,000 square kilometres; 93,000 square miles) destroyed over 3,000 buildings, and directly killed 33 people.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Bushfire smoke was responsible for an additional 417 deaths.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An estimated three billion terrestrial vertebrates, mostly reptiles, were killed or displaced.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Some species may have been driven to extinction.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In all affected states, air quality dropped to dangerous levels, and smoke moved across the Southern Ocean to impact weather conditions in other continents.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Carbon emissions exceeded 700 million tonnes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Rescue and recovery efforts were immense.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] States of emergency were declared across various regions of New South Wales (NSW) and the north-east to east of Victoria, which were the areas most impacted.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW alone recorded 11,774 fires; six percent of the state burned.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Methods of community damage control included total fire bans and strict evacuation orders.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Australian Defence Force was mobilised to provide manpower and logistical support, and international crews were brought in from New Zealand, Singapore, Canada and the United States.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An air tanker, helicopters and fire trucks crashed in rescue efforts, resulting in the deaths of several crew members.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The last major fire in Victoria was contained on 27 February 2020, and all fires in New South Wales were extinguished by 2 March.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The total economic loss was estimated being at least $100 billion, far and away the costliest natural disaster in Australian history.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Tourism sector revenues fell by $2.8 billion.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There was considerable debate regarding the underlying cause of the intensity and scale of the fires, including the role of fire management practices and climate change.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires attracted significant international attention.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An estimated $500 million was donated by the public, international organisations, public figures and celebrities for victim relief and wildlife recovery.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Convoys of donated food, clothing and livestock feed were sent to affected areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In eastern and north-eastern Victoria large areas of forest burnt out of control for four weeks before the fires emerged from the forests in late December, taking lives, threatening many towns and isolating Corryong and Mallacoota.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A state of disaster was declared for East Gippsland.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Significant fires occurred in the Adelaide Hills and Kangaroo Island in South Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Moderately affected areas were south-eastern Queensland and areas of south-western Western Australia, with a few areas in Tasmania and the ACT being mildly impacted.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 November 2019, catastrophic fire danger was declared in the Greater Sydney region for the first time since the introduction of this level in 2009 and a total fire ban was in place for seven regions of New South Wales, including Greater Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Illawarra and Greater Hunter areas also experienced catastrophic fire dangers, and so did other parts of the state, including the already fire ravaged parts of northern New South Wales.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The political ramifications of the fire season have been significant.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 14 January 2020, 18.626 million hectares (46.03 million acres) was burnt or is burning across all Australian states and territories.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Ecologists from the University of Sydney estimated 480 million mammals, birds, and reptiles were lost since September with concerns that entire species of plants and animals may have been wiped out by bushfire, later expanded to more than a billion.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Since the start of the season, the ongoing bushfires have destroyed 2,176 homes, as well as 48 facilities and more than 2,000 outbuildings in New South Wales alone.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Twenty-five people were confirmed to have been killed in New South Wales since October.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The latest fatality reported was on 23 January 2020 following the death of a man near Moruya.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In New South Wales, the fires burnt through more land than any other blazes in the past 25 years, in addition to being the state's worst bushfire season on record.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW also experienced the longest continuously burning bushfire complex in Australia's history, having burnt more than 4 million hectares (9,900,000 acres), with 70-metre-high (230 ft) flames being reported.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In comparison, the 2018 California wildfires consumed 800,000 hectares (2,000,000 acres) and the 2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires burnt 900,000 hectares (2,200,000 acres) of land.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Whereas these bushfires are regarded by the NSW Rural Fire Service as the worst bushfire season in memory for that state, the 1974 bushfires were nationally much larger consuming 117 million hectares (290 million acres; 1,170,000 square kilometres; 450,000 square miles).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] However, due to their lower intensity and remote location, the 1974 fires caused around A$5 million (approximately A$36.5 million in 2020) in damages.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019 the New South Wales Government declared a state of emergency after record-breaking temperatures and prolonged drought exacerbated the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to safety concerns and significant public pressure, New Year's Eve fireworks displays were cancelled across New South Wales including highly popular events at Campbelltown, Liverpool, Parramatta, and across Sydney's Northern Beaches, and as well in the nation's capital of Canberra.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As temperatures reached 49 °C (120 °F), the New South Wales Premier Gladys Berejiklian called a fresh seven-day state of emergency with effect from 9am on 3 January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, a Lockheed C-130 Hercules air tanker crashed at Peak View near Cooma while waterbombing a blaze, resulting in the death of the three American crew members on board.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] It was one of eleven large air tankers brought to Australia for the fire season from Canada and US.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An investigation is underway by the ATSB to determine the cause of the accident.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Reaching the crash site proved difficult due to the active bushfires in the area.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The crash site was located in dense bushland, and spanned approximately one kilometre.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] To describe emerging fire trends the study by Lucas and others defined two new fire weather categories, "very extreme" and "catastrophic".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The number of "extreme" fire danger days generally increases 5-25% by 2020 for the low scenarios and 15-65% for the high scenarios.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In April 2019 a group of former Australian fire services chiefs warned that Australia was not prepared for the upcoming fire season.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] They called on the next prime minister to meet the former emergency service leaders "who will outline, unconstrained by their former employers, how climate change risks are rapidly escalating".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In August 2019 the federally funded Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC published a seasonal outlook report which advised of "above normal fire potential" for southern and southeast Queensland, the east coast areas of New South Wales and Victoria, for parts of Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019, the Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC updated their advice of "above normal fire potential".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Australian National University reported that the area burned in 2019–2020 was "well below average", pointing out that 30 million hectares less than the Australian annual average burned that year.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] More specifically, the early part of the season (2019) had "near average" burn area, whereas the area burned in the late part of the season (2020) was "unusually low".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSW statutory Bush Fire Danger Period normally begins on 1 October and continues through until 31 March.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In 2019–20, the fire season started early with drought affecting 95 percent of the state and persistent dry and warm conditions across the state.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Twelve local government areas started the Bush Fire Danger Period two months early, on 1 August 2019, and nine more started on 17 August 2019.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 September, the northern parts of the state experienced extreme fire dangers.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At the Port Macquarie suburb of Crestwood a fire started on 26 October from a dry electrical storm.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers were delayed the following day in attempts to bring the fire burning in swampland to the south west of Port Macquarie under control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A back burn on 28 October got away from New South Wales Rural Fire Service (NSWRFS) volunteers after a sudden wind change pushing the fire south towards Lake Cathie and west over Lake Innes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Port Macquarie and surrounding areas were blanketed in thick smoke on 29 October with ongoing fire activity over the following week caused the sky to have an orange glow.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] During this time the Lindfield Park fire burning in dry peat swamp flared up and threatened homes at Sovereign Hills and crossed the Pacific Highway at Sancrox.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the Carrai Plateau west of Kempsey, a fire burnt in wilderness areas where locked up and poorly maintained fire trails made combating it difficult.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire joined up with the Stockyard Creek fire and together with the Coombes Gap fire and swept east towards Willawarrin, Temagog, Birdwood, Yarras, Bellangary, Kindee and Upper Rollands Plains.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Land around Nowendoc and Yarrowich was also burnt.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire burnt more than 40,000 hectares (98,842 acres), destroying numerous homes and claiming the lives of three people.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] North-west of Harrington near the Cattai Wetlands a fire started on 28 October, this fire threatened the towns of Harrington, Crowdy Head and Johns River as it burnt north towards Dunbogan.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] This fire claimed one life at Johns River, where it also destroyed homes, and burnt more than 12,000 hectares (29,653 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At Hillville, a fire grew large due to hot and windy conditions, resulting in disorder in the nearby town of Taree, to the north.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Buses were called in early to take students home before the fire threat became too dangerous.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 9 November, the fire reached Old Bar and Wallabi Point, threatening many properties.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The following two days saw the fire reach Tinonee and Taree South, threatening the Taree Service Centre.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers dropped water on the facility to protect it.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire briefly turned in the direction of Nabiac before wind pushed it towards Failford.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Other communities affected included Rainbow Flat, Khappinghat, Kooringhat and Purfleet.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A spot fire jumped into Ericsson Lane, threatening businesses.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At Dingo Tops National Park a small fire turned into a massive bushfire emergency as it impacted the small village of Bobin; numerous homes and the Bobin Public School were destroyed in the fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fourteen homes were lost on one street in Bobin.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSWRFS sent out alerts to people in Killabakh, Upper Lansdowne, Kippaxs, Elands, and Marlee to monitor conditions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] 2019 Rally Australia, planned to be the final round of the 2019 World Rally Championship, was a motor racing event scheduled to be held in Coffs Harbour across 14–17 November.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A week before the rally was due to begin, the bushfire began to affect the region surrounding Coffs Harbour, with event organisers shortening the event in response to the deteriorating conditions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] With the situation worsening, repeated calls from competitors (most of which were European-based) to cancel the event prevailed with the event cancelled on 12 November.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late December 2019, fires started on both sides of the Pacific Highway around the Coopernook region.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] They burnt 278 hectares (687 acres) before they were brought under control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire in November at Gospers Mountain in the Wollemi National Park burnt over 496,976 ha (1,228,050 acres) and threatened homes in the Hawkesbury and Lithgow areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was projected to burn towards the Central Coast and potentially threaten properties in Wisemans Ferry and other townships.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In an attempt to protect the Blue Mountains from the Gospers Mountain bushfire, firefighters commenced a large backburn on 14 December from the corner of Mt Wilson and Bells Line of Road.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The backburn quickly grew out of control, jumping across Mt Wilson Road and threatening houses in Mount Wilson.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 15 December, the escaped backburn impacted Mount Tomah, Berambing and Bilpin.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed numerous houses and buildings in this area and spread into the Grose Valley.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 19 December the RFS Mt Wilson Backburn escape impacted on the Darling Causeway between Mount Victoria and Bell, it later jumped the Darling Causeway and impacted the Grose Valley and the fire would be split into two fires: Grose Valley fire and Gospers Mountain fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 21 December, a catastrophic day, the Mt Wilson Backburn (the southern part of which was now designated the "Grose Valley fire") impacted Mount Victoria, Blackheath, Bell, Clarence, Dargan and Bilpin with resultant destruction of dozens of homes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the same day the escaped RFS Mt Wilson Backburn fire moved towards Kurrajong.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Further buildings were destroyed as a result of backburning operations in Blackheath along Evans Lookout Road.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 15 December, the "Gospers Mountain fire" had grown to 350,000 hectares (860,000 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There have been persistent myths that the "Gospers Mountain Fire" was the largest fire from a single ignition source in Australian history.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Gospers Mountain Fire was a result of multiple ignition points, the majority of which, were the result of large scale strategic backburning operations that escaped control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The estimated total area burnt by escaped backburning around the Gospers Mountain Fire is over 130,000 hectares.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Whilst the original ignition may have been caused by lightning, the subsequent, separate ignitions caused by RFS backburning contributed greatly to the spread of the fire and the impacted the ability of the RFS to deploy sufficient resources to defend communities.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 November, under Sydney's first ever catastrophic fire conditions, a fire broke out in the Lane Cove National Park south of Turramurra.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Under strong winds and extreme heat the fire spread rapidly, growing out of control and impacting the suburban interface across South Turramurra.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] One house caught alight in Lyon Avenue, but was saved by quick responding firefighters.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As further crews arrived and worked to protect properties, a C-130 Air Tanker made several fire retardant drops directly over firefighters and houses, saving the rest of the suburb.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was ultimately brought under control several hours later, with one firefighter injured suffering a broken arm.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Because of the bushfires occurring in the surrounding regions, the Sydney metropolitan area suffered from dangerous smoky haze for several days throughout December.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On some days, the air quality was eleven times the hazardous level, making it even worse than New Delhi's.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The conditions were likened to "smoking 32 cigarettes" by Associate Professor Brian Oliver, a respiratory diseases scientist at the University of Technology Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 10 December the fire impacted the south-western Sydney suburbs of Nattai and Oakdale, followed by Orangeville and Werombi, threatening hundreds of houses and resulting in the destruction of one building.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire continued to flare up sporadically, coming out of the dense bush and threatening properties in Oakdale and Buxton on 14 and 15 December.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire moved south-east towards the populated areas of the Southern Highlands and impacted the townships of Balmoral, Buxton, Bargo, Couridjah and Tahmoor in far south-western Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Substantial property losses occurred across these areas, in particular multiple fire trucks were overrun by fire, with several firefighters taken to hospital and two airlifted in critical condition.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Later that night, two firefighters were killed when a tree fell onto the road and their tanker rolled, injuring three other crew members.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The situation deteriorated on 21 December when the fire changed direction and attacked Balmoral and Buxton once more from the opposite side, with major property losses in both areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On New Year's Eve there were fears of this fire impacting the towns of Mittagong, Braemar, and surrounding areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 31 December, a grass fire broke out in the sloped woodlands of Prospect Hill, in Western Sydney, where it headed north towards Pemulwuy along the Prospect Highway.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire impacted a large industrial area and threatened numerous properties before being brought under control by 9:30pm.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 10 hectares (25 acres) and a number of historic Monterey pine trees were burnt.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Sydney City fireworks display was allowed to continue with a special exemption from fire authorities, despite protests.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite warnings from authorities, numerous fires were sparked across Sydney as a result of illegal fireworks, including a blaze which threatened properties at Cecil Hills in Sydney's south west.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 4 January, Sydney's western suburb Penrith recorded its hottest day on record at 48.9 °C (120.0 °F) making it the hottest place on Earth at the time.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 January, a fire broke out in bushland at Voyager Point in Sydney's south-west, spreading rapidly under a strong southerly wind and impacting numerous houses in Voyager Point and Hammondville.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As the fire moved north, authorities closed the M5 Motorway due to smoke conditions and prepared for the fire to impact the New Brighton housing estate.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters on the ground assisted by numerous waterbombing aircraft held the fire south of the motorway and prevented any property losses, containing the fire to 60 hectares (150 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late October, a number of fires started in remote bushland near Lake Burragorang in the Kanangra-Boyd National Park south-west of Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to the extreme isolation of the area and rugged inaccessible terrain, firefighters struggled to contain the fires as they began to spread through the dense bushland.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] These multiple fires ultimately all merged to become the Green Wattle Creek fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire continued to grow in size and intensity, burning towards the township of Yerranderie.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters undertook backburning around the town whilst helicopters and fixed wing aircraft worked to control the spread of the fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire passed Yerranderie but continued to burn through the national park towards south-western Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 December under severe weather conditions, the fire jumped the Lake Burragorang and began burning towards populated areas within the Wollondilly area.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 19 December, the fire continued east towards the Hume Highway (resulting in its closure for several hours), impacting the township of Yanderra.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over the following days as the fire continued to progress to the south east, both Yerrinbool and Hill Top were threatened by the fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As well as expanding to the south and east, the fire also spread in a westerly direction, headed towards Oberon.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Oberon Correctional Centre was evacuated in anticipation of the advancing fire impact along its western flank.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 2 January, the fire hit the popular and historic Jenolan Caves area, destroying multiple buildings including the local fire station.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The centrepiece of the precinct, Jenolan Caves House, was saved.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A blaze on the South Coast started off at Currowan and travelled up to the coastline after jumping across the Princes Highway, threatening properties around Termeil.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents in Bawley Point, Kioloa, Depot Peach, Pebbly Beach, North Durras and Pretty Beach were told to either evacuate to Batemans Bay or Ulladulla or stay to protect their property.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, the Currowan fire was burning between Batemans Bay in the south, Nowra in the north, and east of Braidwood in the west.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire had burnt more than 258,000 hectares (640,000 acres) and was out of control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Currowan fire had merged with the Tianjara fire in the Morton National Park to the south west of Nowra; and the Charleys Forest fire had grown along the fire's western flank; and on the fire's southern flank, the fire had merged with the Clyde Mountain fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 26 December, the Clyde Mountain fire was burning on the southern side of the Kings Highway, into the Buckenbowra and Runnyford areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Around 4 am on 31 December, the fire had crossed the Princes Highway near Mogo, and the highway was closed between Batemans Bay and Moruya.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Around 7 am on 31 December, the fire impacted the southern side of Batemans Bay, causing the loss of around ten businesses and damage to many others.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire also crossed the Princes Highway in the vicinity of Round Hill and impacted the residential suburbs of Catalina, as well as beach suburbs from Sunshine Bay to Broulee.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents and holiday makers were forced to flee to the beaches.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the 23 January this fire escalated back to emergency level as the blaze roared towards the coastal town of Moruya, a town largely unaffected by bushfires in recent weeks.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At nearby Lake Conjola, numerous homes were lost as the embers jumped across the lake, landing in gutters and lighting up houses.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On one street there were only four houses still standing.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, at least two people died and a woman was missing.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Isolated hamlets of Bendalong and Manyana and Cunjurong Point were additionally ablaze, with holiday-makers evacuated on 3 January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 6 January 2020, all were still without power.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 5 January 2020, in the Bega Valley Shire, the border fire that started in north-eastern Victoria was burning north into New South Wales towards the major town of Eden, and had impacted the settlements of Wonboyn and surrounding areas including Kiah, Lower Towamba and parts of Boydtown.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Part of the fire was burning in inaccessible country and continued to head in a north-westerly direction towards Bombala as well as northerly to just south of Nethercote.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire had burnt more than 60,000 hectares (150,000 acres) and was out of control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 December, the Green Valley fire burning east of Albury near Talmalmo (which had started the day prior) developed into an unprecedented fire event for the Snowy Valleys as a result of extreme local conditions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke plume rose to an estimated 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) and developed a pyro-cumulonimbus cloud, becoming a firestorm.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The result was extreme, the wind was described by crews on the ground as in excess of 100 km/h (62 mph), with spot fires starting over 5 km (3.1 mi) ahead of the main fire front.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Firefighters described what they believed to be a tornado generated by the fire storm, which began flattening trees and flipped a small fire vehicle.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The tornado then impacted a crew of firefighters working to protect a property, flipping their tanker over and trapping the crew inside, who were then overrun by fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] One firefighter was killed with multiple others injured, with one airlifted to Melbourne and two to Sydney.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Dunns Road fire was believed to have been started by a lightning strike on 28 December in a private pine plantation near Adelong.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In the Snowy Valleys local government area, by 2 January 2020 the Dunns Road fire had burnt south of the Snowy Mountains Highway in the Ellerslie Range near Kunama.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Over 130,000 hectares (320,000 acres) was burnt and the fire was out of control.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The NSWRFS issued an evacuation order to residents in the Batlow and Wondalga areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Residents and visitors to the Kosciuszko National Park were evacuated and the national park was closed.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] 155 inmates from the Mannus Correctional Centre near Tumbarumba were evacuated.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January 2020, the Dunns Road fire burnt from Batlow into Kosciuszko National Park, burning much of the northern part of the park.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire caused significant damage, severely damaging the Selwyn Snow Resort, destroying structures in the town of Cabramurra and almost completely destroying the heritage-listed precinct (and birthplace of skiing in Australia) of Kiandra.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Kiandra's historic former courthouse was left with only its walls standing after a fire so hot that the glass and aluminium in the windows melted.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A number of high country huts, including Wolgal Hut and Pattinsons Hut near Kiandra, were also feared to have been destroyed.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 11 January three fires had merged – the Dunns Road fire, the East Ournie Creek, and the Riverina's Green Valley fire – and had created a 600,000-hectare (1,482,632-acre) "mega-fire", burning south of the Snowy Mountains.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, a Lockheed C-130 Hercules large air tanker crashed near Cooma while waterbombing a blaze, resulting in the death of the three American crew members on board.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 21 November, lightning strikes ignited a series of fires in East Gippsland, initially endangering the communities of Buchan, Buchan South and Sunny Point.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December, the Marthavale-Barmouth Spur expanded, greatly endangering the community of Tambo Crossing.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The first day of two-day cricket tour match between a Victoria XI and New Zealand in Melbourne was cancelled due to extreme heat conditions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 December, there were three active fires in East Gippsland with a combined area of more than 130,000 hectares (320,000 acres), and another in the north-east of the state near Walwa heading south-east towards Cudgewa.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An evacuation warning was issued for the East Gippsland town of Goongerah, which is surrounded by high-value old growth forests, as well as Cudgewa.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the same day, a fire broke out in the Plenty Gorge Parklands, situated in Melbourne's northern suburbs between Bundoora, Mill Park, South Morang, Greensborough and Plenty.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires reached the town of Mallacoota by around 8 am AEDT on 31 December 2019.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 11 am AEDT 31 December, fires had begun to approach the vacation town of Lakes Entrance.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite the recommendation that large portions of East Gippsland be evacuated, approximately 30,000 holiday makers chose to remain in the region.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 4,000 people, including 3,000 tourists, remained in Mallacoota as the fire began making its closest approach to the town, cutting off roads in the process; Mallacoota had not been issued with an evacuation warning on 29 December.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January, approximately 1,160 people from Mallacoota were evacuated on naval vessels HMAS *Choules* and *MV Sycamore*.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Emergency Management Commissioner Andrew Crisp stated that 780,000 hectares (1,900,000 acres) had burnt including 100,000 hectares (250,000 acres) near Corryong in the state's north-east and that fifty fires were burning.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 3 January, Premier Andrews said two people were confirmed dead from the East Gippsland fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 January Premier Andrews said that bushfires had burnt through 1.2 million hectares (3 million acres) in Victoria's east and north-east and that 200 homes were confirmed lost.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 January, two bushfires were burning at emergency level in Victoria despite milder conditions, one about 8 km east of Abbeyard and the other in East Gippsland affecting Tamboon, Tamboon South and Furnel.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 January, there were still 12 fires burning in Victoria, the strongest in East Gippsland and the north-east.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Buldah fire in East Gippsland was at watch and act level and the rest were on advice level.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Most of the 44 fires sparked by dry lightning were quickly dealt with by firefighters.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Heavy rain in the Melbourne region brought little relief to bushfire-affected regions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Premier Daniel Andrews said that the rains could bring new dangers for firefighters, including landslides.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 30 January, four days of hot weather were forecast for Victoria, New South Wales and South Australia bringing high fire danger with several uncontrolled bushfires still burning.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 7 September 2019 multiple out of control blazes threatened townships across south-eastern and northern Queensland, destroying eleven houses in Beechmont, seven houses in Stanthorpe, and one house at Mareeba.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On the following day the heritage-listed lodge and cabins at the iconic Australian nature-based Binna Burra Lodge were destroyed in the bushfire that consumed residential houses in Beechmont the previous day.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire impacted the Peregian Beach area on 9 September, on the Sunshine Coast, severely damaging ten houses.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019 Peregian Springs and the surrounding areas came under threat by bushfires for the second time in a couple of months.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] No homes were confirmed lost in this bushfire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Due to deteriorating fire conditions and fires threatening homes across the state, on 9 November a State of Fire Emergency was declared across 42 local government areas across southern, central, northern and far-northern Queensland.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 11 November a fire started in the Ravensbourne area near Toowoomba, which burnt through over 20,000 hectares (49,000 acres) of bush across several days, destroying six houses.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 8 am the air quality in Brisbane reached unprecedentedly poor levels (Woolloongabba PM2.5 238.8 μg/m3).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Queensland's chief health officer, Dr Jeanette Young, urged residents to stay indoors and to not physically exert themselves.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 November a water bombing helicopter crashed while fighting the blazes threatening the small community of Pechey.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the Bell 214 helicopter was completely destroyed, the pilot walked away with minor injuries.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 23 November the state of fire emergency was revoked and extended fire bans were put in place in local government areas that were previously affected under this declaration.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 6 December a house fire broke out in Bundamba and quickly spread to nearby bushland and was placed under a watch and act alert by the Queensland Fire and Emergency Services that afternoon.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The following day, after worsening conditions, the fire was upgraded to an emergency warning and began to threaten homes in the local community.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed a shipping container filled with fireworks, and residents within the 3-square-kilometre (1.2 sq mi) exclusion zone were ordered to evacuate.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 8 November a bushfire broke out in forestry to the west of the township of Jimna, causing Queensland Fire and Emergency services to issue a "watch and act" alert.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire caused the evacuation of the entire town.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 11 November 2019 an emergency bushfire warning was issued for Port Lincoln in the Eyre Peninsula, with an uncontrolled fire traveling towards the town.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The South Australian Country Fire Service ordered ten water bombers to the area to assist 26 ground crews at the scene.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] SA Power Networks disconnected power to the town.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire broke out on Yorke Peninsula on 20 November 2019 and threatened the towns of Yorketown and Edithburgh.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] It destroyed at least eleven homes and burnt approximately 5,000 hectares (12,000 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire was believed to have started from a sparking electrical transformer.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A Boeing 737 water-bombing aircraft from New South Wales in addition to South Australian Air Tractor AT-802s were used to protect the town of Edithburgh.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December fires took hold in the Adelaide Hills, and near Cudlee Creek in the Mount Lofty Ranges.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Initial south-easterly winds put the towns of Lobethal and Lenswood in the line of the fire, and by the next morning the winds had changed to north-north-west, threatening other towns.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires killed one person, more than 70 houses were destroyed, as well as over 400 outbuildings and 200 cars.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires are still burning and the yearly Christmas celebrations at Lobethal were cancelled.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Also on 20 December, an out-of-control bushfire took hold near Angle Vale, starting from the Northern Expressway and burning through Buchfelde and across the Gawler River.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At 11:07 am ACDT the fire was burning under catastrophic weather conditions and an emergency warning was issued for Hillier, Munno Para Downs, Kudla, Munno Para West and Angle Vale.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Another emergency warning was issued on 3 January for a fire near Kersbrook.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] At its largest extent, the warning area overlapped with areas that a few days earlier had been in warnings for the Cudlee Creek fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Water bombers delivered 21 loads in just over an hour before darkness fell, and 150 firefighters on 25 trucks plus bulk water carriers and earthmoving equipment limited the advance of the fire to 18 hectares (44 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On Kangaroo Island starting in the Flinders Chase National Park, the Ravine bushfire burnt in excess of 15,000 hectares (37,000 acres) and a bushfire emergency warning was issued on 3 January 2020 as the fire advanced towards Vivonne Bay and the town of Parndana was evacuated.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 4 January it was confirmed at least two people died.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 6 January 2020 approximately 170,000 hectares (420,000 acres), representing about a third of the island, had been burnt.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Fires remained burning out of control, with firefighters working to contain and control fires before potentially hot windy weather scheduled for later in the week.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Following fire damage to a water treatment plant, residents were asked to conserve water and some water was carted into island towns.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] There were concerns for the future of threatened wildlife, such as glossy black cockatoos, Kangaroo Island dunnarts, and koalas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Authorities stated that any koalas taken to the mainland for treatment cannot return to the island in case they bring diseases back with them.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Two bushfires burnt in Geraldton on 13 November, damaging homes and small structures.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A fire broke out in Yanchep at 2:11 pm on 11 December, immediately triggering an emergency warning for Yanchep and Two Rocks.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire led to a service station exploding.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 12 December, temperatures in excess of 40 °C (104 °F) exacerbated the fire, and the emergency warning area doubled including parts of Guilderton and Brenton Bay further north.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 13 December, increased temperature conditions resulted in the fire burning in excess of 5,000 hectares (12,000 acres), with the fire front over 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) in length.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 13 December 2019, the emergency warning area stretched from Yanchep north to Lancelin over 40 km (25 mi) away.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 16 December, the fire was considered contained and the alert downgraded to watch and act.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Approximately 13,000 hectares (32,000 acres) were burnt; only two buildings were damaged, both within the first day of the fire starting.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December fires in the region around Norseman blocked access to the Eyre Highway and the Nullarbor and caused the highways of the region to be blocked, so as to prevent any recurrence of the 2007 death of truck drivers on the Great Eastern Highway.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Between 26 December 2019 and 1 January 2020, as a result of a lightning strike, a fire tore through 40,000 hectares (99,000 acres) of land in Stirling Range National Park in the southwest of the state, burning more than half of the park.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The pyrocumulus cloud from the fires could be seen 80 km (50 mi) south in Albany.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By New Year's Day 2020 a crew of 200 firefighters brought the fire back to advice level without any loss of life or major property damage (a park ranger hut and hiking tracks were destroyed).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] However, conservationists raised concerns for the potential loss of rare and unique flora and fauna that live in the park, which contains over 1500 such species within its boundaries, including a rare population of quokkas (one of few in mainland Western Australia).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A local politician, firefighters, farmers and tourism operators called on Western Australian Emergency Minister Fran Logan to invest in local firefighting assets for the area in order to make sure the tourist destination was properly protected.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In late October 2019, four bushfires were burning near Scamander, Elderslie and Lachlan.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Emergency warnings were issued at Lulworth, Bothwell and Lachlan.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A large fire near Swansea also burnt over 4,000 hectares (9,900 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Lightning strikes subsequently started multiple fires in Southwest Tasmania.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 20 December 2019, a fire was started in the north east, which spread to 15,000 hectares (37,000 acres) and destroyed one home; a man was charged with starting the fire.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Two fires continued to burn in January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] A fire in the Fingal Valley, in north-eastern Tasmania, started on 29 December, and a fire at Pelham, north of Hobart, started on 30 December.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 16 January 2020 the Fingal fire had burnt over 20,000 hectares (49,000 acres) and the Pelham fire over 2,100 hectares (5,200 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In the Australian Capital Territory (ACT), the national capital Canberra was blanketed by thick bushfire smoke on New Year's Day from bushfires burning nearby in New South Wales.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] That day the air quality in the capital was the worst of any city in the world, at around 23 times the threshold to be considered hazardous.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Conditions continued the next day, and Australia Post stopped postal deliveries in the ACT to keep workers safe from smoke.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The first death directly linked to the poor air quality was also recorded on 2 January.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An elderly women had been travelling from Brisbane to Canberra by plane, when she exited the plane onto the smoke-flooded tarmac, she suffered respiratory distress and then died.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 2 January 2020, the ACT declared a state of alert; that was extended on 12 January as the merged Dunns Road fire burnt seven kilometres (four miles) from the Territory's south-west border.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] From at least 6 January a bushfire near Hospital Hill in the Namadgi National Park had started; it was extinguished on 9 January.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 22 January a bushfire started in Pialligo Redwood Forest; it reached emergency level threatening Beard and Oaks Estate.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The next day a second bushfire started, the Kallaroo Fire, which later during the day merged with the Redwood Forest fire forming the Beard Fire; the fire jumped the Molonglo River and threatened the suburbs of Beard, Harman and Oaks Estate as it burnt 424 hectares (1,050 acres).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fire destroyed 1 facility, 4 outbuildings and 3 vehicles.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 27 January a bushfire in the Orroral Valley in the Namadgi National Park started.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] ACT Emergency Services Minister Mick Gentleman reported, on behalf of the Department of Defence, that the fire had been started by a landing light on a Defence helicopter, while it was conducting routine aerial reconnaissance and ground clearance work to support local firefighters.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By the morning of 28 January the fire had grown to 2,575 hectares in size and was 9 kilometres from the town of Tharwa.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] An emergency warning was declared for Tharwa and the southern suburbs of Canberra just after 1:30pm AEST on 28 January.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Chief Minister Andrew Barr described the fire as the biggest threat to Canberra since the 2003 Canberra bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The Northern Territory went through a relatively average annual bushfire season with respect to area of land burnt, in comparison to the scale of bushfires witnessed in other areas of Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Despite this, approximately 6.8 million hectares (17 million acres) was burnt, an area which contributed significantly to the total area burnt by bushfires in the nation.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Five homes were lost to bushfires in the Territory.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the full extent of the current bushfires is yet to be measured, there have been a number of large scale bushfires recorded in Australian history.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The widespread 1938-9 fires in Victoria, NSW, South Australia and the ACT similarly gained international headlines when the fires entered the Sydney suburbs, as did the 1994 eastern seaboard fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The 1851 Black Thursday bushfires shocked colonial Australia with their ferocity, burning a quarter of what is now Victoria (around five million hectares).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] Lesser known is that about 117 million hectares, or 15 per cent of Australia's land mass, experienced fire in the summer of 1974–5.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] NSW was again badly affected, and three people killed, however the fires were mainly in sparsely populated inland areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In mid-December 2019, a NASA analysis revealed that since 1 August, the New South Wales and Queensland bushfires had emitted 250 million tonnes (280 million short tons) of carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] As of 2 January 2020, NASA estimated that 306 million tonnes (337 million short tons) of CO2 had been emitted.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By comparison, in 2018, Australia's total carbon emissions were equivalent to 535 million tonnes (590 million short tons) of CO2.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] While the carbon emitted by the fires would normally be reabsorbed by forest regrowth, this would take decades and might not happen at all if prolonged drought has damaged the ability of forests to fully regrow.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] In December 2019, the air quality index (AQI) around Rozelle, a west suburb of Sydney, hit 2,552 or more than 12 times the hazardous level of 200.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The level of fine particle matters, known and measured globally as PM2.5, around Sydney was also measured at 734 micrograms (0.01133 gr) or the equivalent of 37 cigarettes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 1 January 2020, the AQI around Monash, a suburb of Canberra, was measured at 4,650, or more than 23 times hazardous level and peaked at 7,700.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On New Year's Day 2020 in New Zealand, a blanket of smoke from the Australian fires covered the whole South Island, giving the sky an orange-yellow haze.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] People in Dunedin reported smelling smoke in the air.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The MetService stated that the smoke would not have any adverse affects on the weather or temperature in the country.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke moved over the North Island the following day, but began breaking up and was less intense than over the South Island the previous day; meanwhile, South Pacific winds South Pacific Ocean dissipated the smoke over the South Island.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The smoke affected glaciers in the country, giving a brown tint to the snow.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] On 5 January 2020, more smoke wafted over the North Island, turning the sky in Auckland orange.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] By 7 January 2020, the smoke was carried approximately 11,000 kilometres (6,800 mi) across the South Pacific Ocean to Chile, Argentina, Brazil, and Uruguay.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p01] The fires resulted in agricultural losses of over AUD 5 billion, destroying livestock, crops, wildlife and agricultural infrastructure across vast areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Chris Dickman, a fellow of the Australian Academy of Science from the University of Sydney, estimated on 8 January 2020 that more than one billion animals were killed by bushfires in Australia; while more than 800 million animals perished in New South Wales.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The estimate was based on a 2007 World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) report on impacts of land clearing on Australian wildlife in New South Wales that provided estimates of mammal, bird and reptile population density in the region.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Dickman's calculation had been based on highly conservative estimates and the actual mortality would therefore be higher.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The figure provided by Dickman included mammals (excluding bats), birds, and reptiles; and did not include frogs, insects, or other invertebrates.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Other estimates, which include animals like bats, amphibians and invertebrates, also put the number killed at over a billion.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Ecologists feared some endangered species were driven to extinction by the fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Though bushfires are not uncommon in Australia, they are usually of lower scale and intensity that only affect small parts of the overall distribution of where species live.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Animals that survived a bushfire could still find suitable habitats in the immediate vicinity, which was not the case when an entire distribution is decimated in an intense event.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Besides immediate mortality from the fires, there were on-going mortalities after the fires from starvation, lack of shelter, and attacks from predators such as foxes and cats that are attracted to fire-affected areas to hunt.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On Kangaroo Island, Australia's third largest island and known as Australia's "Galapagos Island", a third of the island was burnt.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Large parts of the island are designated as protected areas and host animals such as sea lions, penguins, kangaroos, koalas, pygmy possums, southern brown bandicoots, Ligurian bees, Kangaroo Island dunnarts and various birds including glossy black cockatoos.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] NASA estimated that the number of dead koalas could be as high as 25,000 or about half the total population of the species on the island.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A quarter of the beehives of the Ligurian honey bees that inhabited the Island were believed to have been destroyed.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Both the Kangaroo Island dunnart and Kangaroo Island subspecies of the glossy black cockatoo are endangered and are only found on Kangaroo Island.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Before the fires, there were only less than 500 Kangaroo Island dunnarts and about 380 Kangaroo Island glossy black cockatoos.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australian magpies, which are known to have the ability to mimic the calls of other birds and animals, were so frequently exposed to the sirens from fire trucks and ambulances caused by the bushfires that a magpie in Newcastle was captured on video mimicking the sound of emergency sirens.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The two primary firefighting agencies for New South Wales, Fire and Rescue NSW and the NSW Rural Fire Service, formed the bulk of the primary response to the fires, mobilising thousands of firefighters and several hundred firefighting vehicles.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] They were heavily supported by the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service and the Forestry Corporation of NSW, who hold jurisdiction over national parks and forests across the state.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Additional local firefighting resources were also utilised from agencies such as Air Services Australia and Sydney Trains.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Despite the substantial loss of property and loss of life, firefighters have so far managed to save over 16,000 structures from direct fire impact in addition to countless lives.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] With brush-tailed rock-wallabies and much of the indigenous wildlife population in parts of New South Wales were left without food or water, the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service airdropped approximately 1,800 kilograms (4,000 lb) vegetables on the known habitats.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A joint operation by the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service and NSW Rural Fire Service was mounted to protect the critically endangered Wollemia pines growing in Wollemi National Park.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Fire retardant was dropped from air tankers, and an irrigation system was installed on the ground by specialist firefighters, who were lowered into the area by winches from helicopters.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 24 December 2019, the Morrison Government announced that volunteer firefighters employed in the Commonwealth public service would be offered at least 20 working days paid leave.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 29 December 2019, it announced that volunteer firefighters who have been called out for more than 10 days would be able to receive financial compensation.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, it announced that it would lease four waterbombing planes including two long-range DC-10s and two medium-range for use by state and territory governments.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 January 2020, the Prime Minister announced the establishment of the National Bushfire Recovery Agency, funded initially with A$2 billion, under the control of former Australian Federal Police Commissioner, Andrew Colvin.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 December 2019, the Australian Defence Force (ADF) commenced *Operation Bushfire Assist* to support state fire services in logistics, planning, capability, and operational support.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 1 January 2020, the ADF deployed additional military staff establishing the Victorian Joint Task Force 646 (Army Reserve 4th Brigade) and the following day the New South Wales Joint Task Force 1110 (Army Reserve 5th Brigade).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 3 January 2020, HMAS *Choules* and MV *Sycamore* evacuated civilians from Mallacoota bound for Westernport.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, following a meeting of the National Security Committee, the Morrison Government announced a compulsory call-out of Army Reserve brigades to deploy up to 3,000 reserve personnel full-time to assist with in the Operation.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Additionally, Defence announced that it would deploy HMAS *Adelaide* to support other Navy ships in evacuations and relief, as well additional Chinook helicopters and military transport aircraft to RAAF Base East Sale.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The same day, Chinook helicopters evacuated civilians from Omeo; and Spartan aircraft evacuated civilians from Mallacoota on 5 January.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 1 December 2019 WWF-Australia launched the "Towards Two Billion Trees" plan to aid the koala bushfire recovery.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It aims to stop excessive tree-clearing, protect the existing trees and forests, and restore native habitat that has been lost.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The ten-point plan for the next ten years foresees to grow 1.56 billion new trees and save 780 million trees.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Political figures from outside Australia including Donald Trump, Cory Booker, Hillary Clinton, Al Gore, Bernie Sanders, Greta Thunberg, and Elizabeth Warren all publicly commented about the fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Some of the aforementioned people have also donated or raised funds.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January 2020, Queen Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh sent a message of condolence to Governor-General David Hurley, sending their "thoughts and prayers to all Australians at this difficult time".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Queen indicated in her message that she was "deeply saddened" to hear of the fires and their devastating impact on the country, and expressed her thanks to emergency service workers.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 8 January 2020, Prince Charles issued a video message expressing his despair at the "appalling horror" of the fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Four deployments totalling 87 Canadian firefighters were sent through the Canadian Interagency Forest Fire Centre.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It was the first time since 2009 that Canadian personnel were deployed to Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Canadian government also sent a CC-17 plane of the Royal Canadian Air Force with 15 personnel on 27 January to further aid with transport and provide airlift support.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The government of Fiji deployed the Fiji Military Forces humanitarian assistance and disaster relief platoon and engineers to assist in the bush fire rehabilitation.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 6 January, French President Emmanuel Macron stated he could help out with the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A team of five French firefighting experts arrived in Australia on 9 January in order to determine possible options for French and European support.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 15 January, the Japanese government sent two C-130 aircraft of the JASDF, along with 70 other Self-Defense Force personnel to assist in transport and other efforts in combating the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The aircraft left Komaki Air Base and flew to RAAF Base Richmond in New South Wales the next day.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 5 January, Malaysia offered its assistance through a statement by Deputy Prime Minister Wan Azizah Wan Ismail.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 13 January, Malaysia officially deployed over forty firefighters to assist with the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Twenty others from government agencies would also be involved with the mission.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Over fifty New Zealanders were deployed to Australia in both direct fire fighting and support roles.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In January 2020, New Zealand also deployed elements of the Royal New Zealand Air Force and New Zealand Army including three NH90 helicopters, two Army combat engineer sections, and a command element.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A specialist six person animal disaster response team were deployed by non-profit Animal Evac New Zealand on 8 January to New South Wales, assisting with wildlife rescue and supported by SAFE.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The team was the first international specialist animal rescuers to arrive and included vets, animal management officers as well as animal disaster and technical animal rescue experts.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A second team of four arrived on 13 January.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The teams partnered with local wildlife centres to successfully rescue and relocate several injured animals. as well as advising residents in fire danger zones on their animal evacuation plans.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Government of Papua New Guinea offered to send 1,000 military and other personnel to Australia to assist with the response to the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australia accepted 100 Papua New Guinea Defence Force personnel.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Philippine Red Cross pledged to donate $100K to Australia, while various Filipino personalities pledged support for the victims of the bush fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The women-led Teduray people of Maguindanao initiated a sacred rain-making ritual for Australian victims, calling on the fire goddess Frayag Sarif's intercession to bring rain to the country.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Singapore deployed two Chinook helicopters and 42 Singapore Armed Forces personnel stationed at Oakey Army Aviation Centre to RAAF Base East Sale in Victoria.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The United Arab Emirates sent 200 volunteers from the Emirates Red Crescent to help fight the fire, including Emirati astronaut Sultan Al Neyadi.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A Twitter campaign and hashtag #mateshelpmates was launched by the Dubai Expo 2020 aiming to raise donations to help those affected by the fires in Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] To increase awareness, Burj Khalifa in Dubai, the world's tallest tower, lit up in solidarity with Australia.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Twenty firefighters from the United States Department of the Interior were deployed to Australia to help combat the fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Fire fighters from other parts of the US also helped with the fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 23 January, three US firefighters died in the crash of a C-130 fire fighting aircraft.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australia is one of the most fire-prone continents on earth, and bushfires form part of the natural cycle of its landscapes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Nonetheless, the political nature of many of the crisis and its associated issues has also resulted in the circulation of large amounts of disinformation regarding the causes of the fire activity, at the neglect of credible scientific research, expert opinion, and previous government inquiries.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The major cause of ignition of fires during the 2019–20 fire crisis in NSW and Victoria is reported to be lightning strikes.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] According to the ABC, arson has been of little impact – accounting for around 1% of NSW blazes and 0.3% of Victorian blazes by 18 January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A likely contributor to the bushfire crisis was the ongoing drought in eastern Australia – the most severe on record for some fire affected areas.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Exacerbating the effects of diminished rainfall in this drought has been a record breaking run of above average monthly temperatures, lasting 36 months to October 2019.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The combination of heat and drought caused critical low fuel moisture content, with Victoria Country Fire Authority Response Controller Gavin Freeman stating that the "underlying dryness" of the bush has led to exceptionally high fire danger.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) stated that on account of projected future climate change, hot days will become more frequent and hotter (very high confidence), and the time in drought is projected to increase over southern Australia (high confidence).
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In October 2019 David Littleproud, the Australian Minister for Water Resources, stated that he "totally accepts" the link between climate change and drought in Australia, as someone who has experienced it first hand.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The crisis has led to calls for more action to combat climate change.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] That said, the Morrison government has received some criticism on its 2030 emission reduction targets.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In the midst of the crisis, conservative politicians and media blamed a lack of prescribed burning and fire break management, although such assertion has subsequently been heavily criticized and disproven by scientific experts.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Accompanying this was the assertion that environmental groups were responsible for the crisis by inhibiting prescribed burning, despite environmental groups holding relatively negligible political power compared to the Liberal and National parties.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Furthermore, the amount of prescribed burning in southeastern Australia has been stated to have increased in recent years, following the recommendation for increased prescribed burning from the 2009 Black Saturday Royal Commission.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Experts suggested that prescribed burning has been more difficult to achieve given recent trends towards warmer and dryer conditions.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Experts have also cast skepticism on the effectiveness of fuel reduction treatments, citing research that suggests that prescribed burning does little to stop bushfire and save property in south east Australia, with climate and weather conditions having primary influence.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Of particular note, the damaging Currowan fire burnt though a large area of Morton National Park subject in 2017 to one of the largest prescribed burns ever successfully conducted in NSW.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The NSW Rural Fire Service referred numerous individuals to the NSW Police; 24 people were charged with arson, allegedly starting bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Approximately one percent of the land burnt in NSW, and 0.03 percent in Victoria, was attributed to arson.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Queensland police reported that 114 fires "were found to be deliberately or maliciously lit".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Incorrect reporting and social media claims about the extent of the fires, its precedents and causes, and matters like funding of fire fighting services have been circulated during the fire season.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Media outlets of differing political allegiances have also disputed each other's coverage.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A number of maps giving an exaggerated impression of Australia's fires have gone viral online, and have been published by major news outlets.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Maps showing "hotspots" were spread online as comprehensive fire maps, giving an exaggerated impression of the extent of fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Photographs of previous Australian bushfires were also being wrongly published as current. and maps that exaggerate the extent of the fires, or include both past and present fires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Incorrect reports were disseminated that the New South Wales Government, led by Premier Gladys Berejiklian, had cut funding to fire services.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] NSW Rural Fire Service Commissioner Shane Fitzsimmons, in response to the funding cut claims, stated "that it is rubbish, it is misinformation, it's being misrepresented and I think it is disgracefully being misrepresented here today".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] He also stated that "not only has our budget not been cut, we are enjoying record budgets.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] We have got more money today than we have ever had before in the history of the organisation".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Debate and controversy continue to surround previous funding cuts to fire management agencies, with other reports noting recent funding cuts to the National Parks and Wildlife Service, which is responsible for the planning and enforcement of prescribed burns in NSW national parks.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Ongoing political and social debate has surrounded many aspects of the 2019–20 Australian fire crisis, particularly regarding the causes and future prevention of such fire activity, and the role of climate change.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The governing Liberal and National parties, accompanied by numerous news outlets associated with climate change denial, firmly deflected responsibility away from the record-breaking drought affecting the country and its associated links to climate change observations and projections.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Conversely, scientific experts have asserted the influence of climate change, drought, prolonged fire weather, and contextualized the limited role of prescribed burning and arson in influencing the crisis.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The political and social response to the crisis has been marked notably by political blame shifting, the circulation of large amounts of disinformation, and political disregard for scientific research, expert opinion, and previous government inquiries.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Further controversy has surrounded Prime Minister Scott Morrison for taking an overseas family holiday to Hawaiʻi, during the bushfires.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] These criticisms also applied to New South Wales Minister for Emergency Services David Elliot, who went for a holiday in Europe.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk was also criticised for holidaying on a cruise ship while fires were active in the state.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] While travelling throughout fire-affected towns in New South Wales, Morrison was filmed attempting to shake the hands of two residents in Cobargo who had refused to shake his outstretched hand.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison was criticised for grabbing and then shaking their hands despite their refusals.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In an interview with Andrew Constance, NSW Liberal MP for Bega, Constance described the incident stating "the locals probably gave him the welcome he probably deserved".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison did not appear concerned with the criticism, later stating, "people are angry, and if people want to direct that at me, that is up to them".
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] On 4 January, volunteer firefighter Paul Parker, from Nelligen, rose to fame after he stopped his firetruck next to a Channel 7 news crew, and used colourful language to denounce what he perceived as an inadequate response by Morrison.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The video became viral over the following days.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Soon after, Morrison released a video on behalf of the Liberal Party regarding deployment of military assets to respond to the bushfire crisis, for which he was widely criticised.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Morrison was further criticised for a "donate" button on a Liberal Party website page which misleadingly led to a donations page for the Liberal Party itself, rather than bushfire relief; the button was later removed.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Philanthropists, corporate organisations, celebrities, and sportspeople donated to various fundraising appeals for bushfire victims and firefighters; estimated to total A$500 million as of 19 January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Following a representative sample, a report issued by the Fundraising Institute of Australia estimated that 53 percent of all adult Australians donated to a bushfire appeal.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Andrew Forrest and his wife, Nicola, donated A$70 million; and the Paul Ramsay Foundation donated A$30 million.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] In November, James Packer pledged A$1 million to support the NSWRFS.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] As the impact of the bushfire season spread, the Crown Resorts Foundation and the Packer Family Foundation pledged a further A$4 million to volunteer fire services in NSW, Victoria and Western Australia – all states in which Crown has resorts.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Murdoch family donated A$5 million; the Micky and Madeleine Arison Family Foundation, A$1.5 million; and donations of A$1 million each were received from the Pratt Foundation, John and Pauline Gandel, Mike Cannon-Brookes, Scott Farquhar, and the Haines and the Perich families.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Leonardo DiCaprio donated US$3 million (A$3.4 million) via Earth Alliance; Kylie Jenner, US$1 million; Ellen DeGeneres, A$1.5 million; and donations of A$1 million were received from Sir Elton John and Chris Hemsworth and family.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] The Wiggles performed a concert on 17 and 18 January, and on 16 February at Stadium Australia in Sydney, the Fire Fight Australia concert will feature local and international acts.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Tennis players, led by Nick Kyrgios, pledged to donate money for every ace served during the Australian summer of tennis.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Many cricket players, such as international representatives Chris Lynn, Glenn Maxwell, D'Arcy Short, Matthew Renshaw and Fawad Ahmed pledged to donate money for every wicket and/or six during the remainder of the Australian cricket season.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Shane Warne and Jeff Thomson, retired Australian cricketers, donated their baggy green Test cricket caps and Thomson also donated a playing vest for online auction.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Warne's cap was purchased by the Commonwealth Bank with a bid of A$1,007,500; and Russell Crowe's Rabbitohs cap was auctioned with a winning bid in excess of A$500,000.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Footballer Mathew Ryan, goalkeeper for Premier League club Brighton & Hove Albion and the Australia national team announced he'll donate $500 for every registered save by an English Premier League goalkeeper on the weekend of 11–12 January 2020.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Australian stars who were playing in the 2019–20 NBA season collectively donated in excess of A$1 million; and Lewis Hamilton, a Formula One driver, donated US$500,000.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Comedian Celeste Barber launched a fundraising appeal with a target of raising A$15,000, however it went on to raise over A$50 million, making it the largest fundraiser ever held on Facebook.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] A telethon conducted with the Sydney New Year's Eve fireworks raised more than A$2 million.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] Multiple media outlets reported that the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) received 86 reports of bushfire-related scams.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It came as increased requests for cash driven donations leveraging crowdfunding platforms like GoFundMe, or as a result of false links posted on Twitter.
[src:climate-change/2019-20-australian-bushfire-season-p02] It prompted some organisations to provide a list of approved and vetted charities online to reduce fraud.
[src:climate-change/2019-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2019.
[src:climate-change/2019-in-climate-change] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
[src:climate-change/2020-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2020.
[src:climate-change/2021-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2021.
[src:climate-change/2021-in-climate-change] among climate experts (2010–2015) reflect that the level of scientific consensus correlates with expertise in climate science.
[src:climate-change/2021-in-climate-change] and a 2021 study concluded that consensus exceeded 99%.
[src:climate-change/2021-in-climate-change] Another 2021 study found that 98.7% of climate experts indicated that the Earth is getting warmer mostly because of human activity.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2022.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] A 2022 study found that the public substantially underestimates the degree of scientific consensus that humans are causing climate change.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] found scientific consensus to range from 98.7–100%.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] Research found that 80–90% of Americans underestimate the prevalence of support for major climate change mitigation policies and climate concern.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] While 66–80% Americans support these policies, Americans estimate the prevalence to be 37–43%.
[src:climate-change/2022-in-climate-change] National political divides on the seriousness of climate change consistently correlate with political ideology, with right-wing opinion being more negative.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In mid-January 2022, the Southern Cone had a severe heat wave, which made the region for a while the hottest place on earth, with temperatures exceeding those of the Middle East.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] This extreme weather event was associated with the Atlantic anticyclone, a particularly intense La Niña phenomenon in the Pacific Ocean, and the regional effects of climate change.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] Several cities had high temperatures over 40 °C (104 °F), setting records for hot days.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In addition, thousands of hectares were destroyed by wildfires across the region.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 10, the temperatures were "particularly anomalous" in the south of the Pampas region and the north of Patagonia.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] According to the *Servicio Meteorológico Nacional* (SMN), that day maximum temperature records were broken in Tres Arroyos 40.7 °C (105.3 °F) and Coronel Pringles 39.6 °C (103.3 °F), along with other records that ranged between 40 °C (104 °F) and 43 °C (109 °F) in the region.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] However, a few days later those same marks were surpassed, with 41.8 °C (107.2 °F) in Tres Arroyos and 40.1 °C (104.2 °F) in Coronel Pringles.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 11, Buenos Aires reached 41.1 °C (106.0 °F), which was the second maximum temperature at the moment since there are systematic records.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] That day almost 45.0 °C (113.0 °F) were registered in San Juan, a few tenths of the monthly record for January.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 12 the city saw 3 heat-related deaths.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 14, Buenos Aires reached 41.5 °C (106.7 °F), which became the second highest temperature recorded, surpassing that recorded three days earlier.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] During the wave, new electric energy consumption records were set at the national level, above 28,000 MW.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 11, a massive blackout affected 700,000 users in the north of Buenos Aires and Greater Buenos Aires.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] To avoid blackouts, the Argentine government asked the industrial sector to reduce energy demand between January 13 and 14, with the aim of being able to provide energy to the home network.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In addition, it decreed teleworking for two days for public employees and urged provincial governments to take similar measures.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] During the most intense week of the heat wave, Argentina imported energy from Brazil and Uruguay.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In the midst of the heat wave, and after important fires registered in the previous weeks, especially in Patagonia, the national government declared a fire emergency throughout the country for one year.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] Fires were recorded in the grasslands and wooded area near Canning and Tristán Suárez, in Ezeiza, which affected some 130 hectares.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In Corrientes, a series of wildfires took place, which consumed around 800,000 hectares, which is equivalent to approximately ten percent of the province.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] Initially, the Uruguayan Institute of Meteorology (INUMET) issued an alert for the heat wave in the north, center and west of the country, but on January 13 it was extended to the entire country.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] That day, the maximum temperature of 42.5 °C (108.5 °F) was reached in the northern city of Salto, being the hottest January day since 1961.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 14, Florida reached 44 °C (111 °F), the highest temperature ever recorded in the country, matching a 1943 record.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] 14 of the 19 departments of the country reached a temperature above 40 °C (104 °F) during the wave.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] The heat wave affected the generation of wind power due to the lack of wind, which resulted in 50% of the electrical energy having to be generated with the thermal power stations of the National Administration of Power Plants and Electrical Transmissions (UTE).
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On January 14, a blackout affected around 25,000 electricity network users in the Canelones, Montevideo and Treinta y Tres departments.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] On that day the country's energy consumption record was broken, reaching 2,139 MW.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] After four days of heat wave, the National Directorate of Firefighters reported more than 100 active fires in different parts of the country, such as Paysandú and Rio Negro.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] This weather event intensified the drought, which had triggered a declaration of "agricultural emergency" in December 2021.
[src:climate-change/2022-southern-cone-heat-wave] In addition, it caused the death of 400,000 chickens, for an estimated value of 1.5 million dollars, due to this, the Ministry of Livestock, Agriculture and Fisheries declared the "poultry emergency".
[src:climate-change/2023-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2023.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Natural forces cause some variability, but the persistent temperature increase shows the progressive influence of human activity.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Present-day **climate change** includes both **global warming**—the ongoing increase in global average temperature—and its wider effects on Earth's climate system.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change in a broader sense also includes previous long-term changes to Earth's climate.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The modern-day rise in global temperatures is driven by human activities, especially fossil fuel (coal, oil and natural gas) burning since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use, deforestation, and some agricultural and industrial practices release greenhouse gases.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These gases absorb some of the heat that the Earth radiates after it warms from sunlight, warming the lower atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Earth's atmosphere now has roughly 50% more carbon dioxide, the main gas driving global warming, than it did at the end of the pre-industrial era, reaching levels not seen for millions of years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change has an increasingly large impact on the environment.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Heat waves and wildfires are becoming more common.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Amplified warming in the Arctic has contributed to thawing permafrost, retreat of glaciers and sea ice decline.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Higher temperatures are also causing more intense storms, droughts, and other weather extremes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Rapid environmental change in mountains, coral reefs, and the Arctic is forcing many species to relocate or become extinct.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Even if efforts to minimize future warming are successful, some effects will continue for centuries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These include ocean heating, ocean acidification and sea level rise.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens people with increased flooding, extreme heat, increased food and water scarcity, more disease, and economic loss.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Human migration and conflict can also be a result.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The World Health Organization calls climate change one of the biggest threats to global health in the 21st century.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Societies and ecosystems will experience more severe risks without action to limit warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Adapting to climate change through efforts like flood control measures or drought-resistant crops partially reduces climate change risks, although some limits to adaptation have already been reached.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Poorer communities are responsible for a small share of global emissions, yet have the least ability to adapt and are most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] , and worsening droughts compromising water supplies.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Many climate change impacts have been observed in the first decades of the 21st century, with 2024 the warmest on record at +1.60 °C (2.88 °F) since regular tracking began in 1850.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Additional warming will increase these impacts and can trigger tipping points, such as melting all of the Greenland ice sheet.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Under the 2015 Paris Agreement, nations collectively agreed to keep warming "well under 2 °C".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] However, with pledges made under the Agreement, global warming would still reach about 2.8 °C (5.0 °F) by the end of the century.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] There is widespread support for climate action worldwide, and most countries aim to stop emitting carbon dioxide.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuels can be phased out by ending their subsidies, conserving energy and switching to energy sources that do not produce significant carbon pollution.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These energy sources include wind, solar, hydro, and nuclear power.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Cleanly generated electricity can replace fossil fuels for powering transportation, heating buildings, and running industrial processes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Carbon can also be removed from the atmosphere, for instance by increasing forest cover and farming with methods that store carbon in soil.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Before the 1980s, it was unclear whether the warming effect of increased greenhouse gases was stronger than the cooling effect of airborne particulates in air pollution.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Scientists used the term *inadvertent climate modification* to refer to human impacts on the climate at this time.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In the 1980s, the terms *global warming* and *climate change* became more common, often being used interchangeably.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Scientifically, *global warming* refers only to increased global average surface temperature, while *climate change* describes both global warming and its effects on Earth's climate system, such as precipitation changes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Over the last few million years the climate cycled through ice ages.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] One of the hotter periods was the Last Interglacial, around 125,000 years ago, where temperatures were between 0.5 °C and 1.5 °C warmer than before the start of global warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This period saw sea levels 5 to 10 metres higher than today.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The most recent glacial maximum 20,000 years ago was some 5–7 °C colder.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This period has sea levels that were over 125 metres (410 ft) lower than today.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Temperatures stabilized in the current interglacial period beginning 11,700 years ago.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This period also saw the start of agriculture.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Historical patterns of warming and cooling, like the Medieval Warm Period and the Little Ice Age, did not occur at the same time across different regions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Temperatures may have reached as high as those of the late 20th century in a limited set of regions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate information for that period comes from climate proxies, such as trees and ice cores.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Around 1850 thermometer records began to provide global coverage.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Between the 18th century and 1970 there was little net warming, as the warming impact of greenhouse gas emissions was offset by cooling from sulfur dioxide emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Sulfur dioxide causes acid rain, but it also produces sulfate aerosols in the atmosphere, which reflect sunlight and cause global dimming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] After 1970, the increasing accumulation of greenhouse gases and controls on sulfur pollution led to a marked increase in temperature.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Ongoing changes in climate have had no precedent for several thousand years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Multiple datasets all show worldwide increases in surface temperature, at a rate of around 0.2 °C per decade.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Not every single year was warmer than the last: internal climate variability processes can make any year 0.2 °C warmer or colder than the average.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] From 1998 to 2013, negative phases of two such processes, Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) and Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) caused a short slower period of warming called the "global warming hiatus".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] After the "hiatus", the opposite occurred, with 2024 well above the recent average at more than +1.5 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This is why the temperature change is defined in terms of a 20-year average, which reduces the noise of hot and cold years and decadal climate patterns, and detects the long-term signal.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] A wide range of other observations reinforce the evidence of warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere is cooling, because greenhouse gases are trapping heat near the Earth's surface, and so less heat is radiating into space.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Warming reduces average snow cover and forces the retreat of glaciers.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] At the same time, warming also causes greater evaporation from the oceans, leading to more atmospheric humidity, and more and heavier precipitation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Plants are flowering earlier in spring, and thousands of animal species have been permanently moving to cooler areas.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Different regions of the world warm at different rates.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The pattern is independent of where greenhouse gases are emitted, because the gases persist long enough to diffuse across the planet.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Since the pre-industrial period, the average surface temperature over land regions has increased almost twice as fast as the global average surface temperature.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This is because oceans lose more heat by evaporation and oceans can store a lot of heat.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The thermal energy in the global climate system has grown with only brief pauses since at least 1970, and over 90% of this extra energy has been stored in the ocean.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The rest has heated the atmosphere, melted ice, and warmed the continents.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere and the North Pole have warmed much faster than the South Pole and Southern Hemisphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The Northern Hemisphere not only has much more land, but also more seasonal snow cover and sea ice.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] As these surfaces flip from reflecting a lot of light to being dark after the ice has melted, they start absorbing more heat.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Local black carbon deposits on snow and ice also contribute to Arctic warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Arctic surface temperatures are increasing between three and four times faster than in the rest of the world.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Melting of ice sheets near the poles weakens both the Atlantic and the Antarctic limb of thermohaline circulation, which further changes the distribution of heat and precipitation around the globe.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The World Meteorological Organization estimates there is almost a 50% chance of the five-year average global temperature exceeding +1.5 °C between 2024 and 2028.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The IPCC expects the 20-year average to exceed +1.5 °C in the early 2030s.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report (2021) included projections that by 2100 global warming is very likely to reach 1.0–1.8 °C under a scenario with very low emissions of greenhouse gases, 2.1–3.5 °C under an intermediate emissions scenario, or 3.3–5.7 °C under a very high emissions scenario.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The warming will continue past 2100 in the intermediate and high emission scenarios, with future projections of global surface temperatures by year 2300 being similar to millions of years ago.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The remaining carbon budget for staying beneath certain temperature increases is determined by modelling the carbon cycle and climate sensitivity to greenhouse gases.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] According to UNEP, global warming can be kept below 2.0 °C with a 50% chance if emissions after 2023 do not exceed 900 gigatonnes of CO2.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This carbon budget corresponds to around 16 years of current emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The climate system experiences various cycles on its own which can last for years, decades or even centuries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For example, El Niño events cause short-term spikes in surface temperature while La Niña events cause short term cooling.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Their relative frequency can affect global temperature trends on a decadal timescale.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Other changes are caused by an imbalance of energy from external forcings.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Examples of these include changes in the concentrations of greenhouse gases, solar luminosity, volcanic eruptions, and variations in the Earth's orbit around the Sun.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] To determine the human contribution to climate change, unique "fingerprints" for all potential causes are developed and compared with both observed patterns and known internal climate variability.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For example, solar forcing—whose fingerprint involves warming the entire atmosphere—is ruled out because only the lower atmosphere has warmed.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Atmospheric aerosols produce a smaller, cooling effect.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Other drivers, such as changes in albedo, are less impactful.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Greenhouse gases are transparent to sunlight, and thus allow it to pass through the atmosphere to heat the Earth's surface.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The Earth radiates it as heat, and greenhouse gases absorb a portion of it.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This absorption slows the rate at which heat escapes into space, trapping heat near the Earth's surface and warming it over time.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While water vapour (≈50%) and clouds (≈25%) are the biggest contributors to the greenhouse effect, they primarily change as a function of temperature and are therefore mostly considered to be feedbacks that change climate sensitivity.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] On the other hand, concentrations of gases such as CO2 (≈20%), tropospheric ozone, CFCs and nitrous oxide are added or removed independently from temperature, and are therefore considered to be external forcings that change global temperatures.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Before the Industrial Revolution, naturally occurring amounts of greenhouse gases caused the air near the surface to be about 33 °C warmer than it would have been in their absence.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Human activity since the Industrial Revolution, mainly extracting and burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, and natural gas), has increased the amount of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In 2022, the concentrations of CO2 and methane had increased by about 50% and 164%, respectively, since 1750.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These CO2 levels are higher than they have been at any time during the last 14 million years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Concentrations of methane are far higher than they were over the last 800,000 years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Global human-caused greenhouse gas emissions in 2019 were equivalent to 59 billion tonnes of CO2.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Of these emissions, 75% was CO2, 18% was methane, 4% was nitrous oxide, and 2% was fluorinated gases.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] CO2 emissions primarily come from burning fossil fuels to provide energy for transport, manufacturing, heating, and electricity.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Additional CO2 emissions come from deforestation and industrial processes, which include the CO2 released by the chemical reactions for making cement, steel, aluminium, and fertilizer.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Methane emissions come from livestock, manure, rice cultivation, landfills, wastewater, and coal mining, as well as oil and gas extraction.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Nitrous oxide emissions largely come from the microbial decomposition of fertilizer.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While methane only lasts in the atmosphere for an average of 12 years, CO2 lasts much longer.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The Earth's surface absorbs CO2 as part of the carbon cycle.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While plants on land and in the ocean absorb most excess emissions of CO2 every year, that CO2 is returned to the atmosphere when biological matter is digested, burns, or decays.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Land-surface carbon sink processes, such as carbon fixation in the soil and photosynthesis, remove about 29% of annual global CO2 emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The ocean has absorbed 20 to 30% of emitted CO2 over the last two decades.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] CO2 is only removed from the atmosphere for the long term when it is stored in the Earth's crust, which is a process that can take millions of years to complete.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Around 30% of Earth's land area is largely unusable for humans (glaciers, deserts, etc.), 26% is forests, 10% is shrubland and 34% is agricultural land.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Deforestation is the main land use change contributor to global warming, as the destroyed trees release CO2, and are not replaced by new trees, removing that carbon sink.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Between 2001 and 2018, 27% of deforestation was from permanent clearing to enable agricultural expansion for crops and livestock.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Another 24% has been lost to temporary clearing under the shifting cultivation agricultural systems.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] 26% was due to logging for wood and derived products, and wildfires have accounted for the remaining 23%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Some forests have not been fully cleared, but were already degraded by these impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Restoring these forests also recovers their potential as a carbon sink.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Local vegetation cover impacts how much of the sunlight gets reflected back into space (albedo), and how much heat is lost by evaporation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For instance, the change from a dark forest to grassland makes the surface lighter, causing it to reflect more sunlight.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Deforestation can also modify the release of chemical compounds that influence clouds, and can change the roughness of Earth’s surface in a way affecting wind speed.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In tropic and temperate areas the net effect is to produce significant warming, and forest restoration can make local temperatures cooler.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] At latitudes closer to the poles, there is a cooling effect as forest is replaced by snow-covered (and more reflective) plains.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Globally, these increases in surface albedo have been the dominant direct influence on temperature from land use change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Thus, land use change to date is estimated to have a slight cooling effect.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Air pollution, in the form of aerosols, affects the climate on a large scale.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Aerosols scatter and absorb solar radiation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] From 1961 to 1990, a gradual reduction in the amount of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface was observed.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This phenomenon is popularly known as *global dimming*, and is primarily attributed to sulfate aerosols produced by the combustion of fossil fuels with heavy sulfur concentrations like coal and bunker fuel.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Smaller contributions come from black carbon (from combustion of fossil fuels and biomass), and from dust.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Globally, aerosols have been declining since 1990 due to pollution controls, meaning that they no longer mask greenhouse gas warming as much.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Aerosols also have indirect effects on the Earth's energy budget.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Sulfate aerosols act as cloud condensation nuclei and lead to clouds that have more and smaller cloud droplets.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These clouds reflect solar radiation more efficiently than clouds with fewer and larger droplets.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] They also reduce the growth of raindrops, which makes clouds more reflective to incoming sunlight.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Indirect effects of aerosols are the largest uncertainty in radiative forcing.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While aerosols typically limit global warming by reflecting sunlight, black carbon in soot that falls on snow or ice can contribute to global warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The resulting excess heat accelerates the melting of ice sheets and glaciers, which in turn contributes significantly to global sea-level rise.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Limiting new black carbon deposits in the Arctic could reduce global warming by 0.2 °C by 2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The effect of decreasing sulfur content of fuel oil for ships since 2020 is estimated to cause an additional 0.05 °C increase in global mean temperature by 2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] As the Sun is the Earth's primary energy source, changes in incoming sunlight directly affect the climate system.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Solar irradiance has been measured directly by satellites, and indirect measurements are available from the early 1600s onwards.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Since 1880, there has been no upward trend in the amount of the Sun's energy reaching the Earth, in contrast to the warming of the lower atmosphere (the troposphere).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The upper atmosphere (the stratosphere) would also be warming if the Sun was sending more energy to Earth, but instead, it has been cooling.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This is consistent with greenhouse gases preventing heat from leaving the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Explosive volcanic eruptions can release gases, dust and ash that partially block sunlight and reduce temperatures, or they can send water vapour into the atmosphere, which adds to greenhouse gases and increases temperatures.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These impacts on temperature only last for several years, because both water vapour and volcanic material have low persistence in the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Volcanic CO2 emissions are more persistent, but they are equivalent to less than 1% of current human-caused CO2 emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Volcanic activity still represents the single largest natural impact (forcing) on temperature in the industrial era.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Yet, like the other natural forcings, it has had negligible impacts on global temperature trends since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The climate system's response to an initial forcing is shaped by feedbacks, which either amplify or dampen the change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] *Self-reinforcing* or *positive* feedbacks increase the response, while *balancing* or *negative* feedbacks reduce it.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The main reinforcing feedbacks are the water-vapour feedback, the ice–albedo feedback, and the net cloud feedback.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The primary balancing mechanism is radiative cooling, as Earth's surface gives off more heat to space in response to rising temperature.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In addition to temperature feedbacks, there are feedbacks in the carbon cycle, such as the fertilizing effect of CO2 on plant growth.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Feedbacks are expected to trend in a positive direction as greenhouse gas emissions continue, raising climate sensitivity.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These feedback processes alter the pace of global warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For instance, warmer air can hold more moisture in the form of water vapour, which is itself a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Warmer air can also make clouds higher and thinner, and therefore more insulating, increasing climate warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The reduction of snow cover and sea ice in the Arctic is another major feedback, this reduces the reflectivity of the Earth's surface in the region and accelerates Arctic warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This additional warming also contributes to permafrost thawing, which releases methane and CO2 into the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Around half of human-caused CO2 emissions have been absorbed by land plants and by the oceans.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This fraction is not static and if future CO2 emissions decrease, the Earth will be able to absorb up to around 70%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] If they increase substantially, it'll still absorb more carbon than now, but the overall fraction will decrease to below 40%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This is because climate change increases droughts and heat waves that eventually inhibit plant growth on land, and soils will release more carbon from dead plants when they are warmer.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The rate at which oceans absorb atmospheric carbon will be lowered as they become more acidic and experience changes in thermohaline circulation and phytoplankton distribution.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Uncertainty over feedbacks, particularly cloud cover, is the major reason why different climate models project different magnitudes of warming for a given amount of emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] A climate model is a representation of the physical, chemical and biological processes that affect the climate system.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Models include natural processes like changes in the Earth's orbit, historical changes in the Sun's activity, and volcanic forcing.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Models are used to estimate the degree of warming future emissions will cause when accounting for the strength of climate feedbacks.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Models also predict the circulation of the oceans, the annual cycle of the seasons, and the flows of carbon between the land surface and the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The physical realism of models is tested by examining their ability to simulate current or past climates.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Past models have underestimated the rate of Arctic shrinkage and underestimated the rate of precipitation increase.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise since 1990 was underestimated in older models, but more recent models agree well with observations.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The 2017 United States-published National Climate Assessment notes that "climate models may still be underestimating or missing relevant feedback processes".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Additionally, climate models may be unable to adequately predict short-term regional climatic shifts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] A subset of climate models add societal factors to a physical climate model.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These models simulate how population, economic growth, and energy use affect—and interact with—the physical climate.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] With this information, these models can produce scenarios of future greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This is then used as input for physical climate models and carbon cycle models to predict how atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases might change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Depending on the socioeconomic scenario and the mitigation scenario, models produce atmospheric CO2 concentrations that range widely between 380 and 1400 ppm.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The environmental effects of climate change are broad and far-reaching, affecting oceans, ice, and weather.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Evidence for these effects comes from studying climate change in the past, from modelling, and from modern observations.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Since the 1950s, droughts and heat waves have appeared simultaneously with increasing frequency.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Extremely wet or dry events within the monsoon period have increased in India and East Asia.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Monsoonal precipitation over the Northern Hemisphere has increased since 1980.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The rainfall rate and intensity of hurricanes and typhoons is likely increasing, and the geographic range likely expanding poleward in response to climate warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The frequency of tropical cyclones has not increased as a result of climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Global sea level is rising as a consequence of thermal expansion and the melting of glaciers and ice sheets.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Sea level rise has increased over time, reaching 4.8 cm per decade between 2014 and 2023.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Over the 21st century, the IPCC projects 32–62 cm of sea level rise under a low emission scenario, 44–76 cm under an intermediate one and 65–101 cm under a very high emission scenario.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Marine ice sheet instability processes in Antarctica may add substantially to these values, including the possibility of a 2-meter sea level rise by 2100 under high emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change has led to decades of shrinking and thinning of the Arctic sea ice.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While ice-free summers are expected to be rare at 1.5 °C degrees of warming, they are set to occur once every three to ten years at a warming level of 2 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 concentrations cause more CO2 to dissolve in the oceans, which is making them more acidic.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Because oxygen is less soluble in warmer water, its concentrations in the ocean are decreasing, and dead zones are expanding.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Greater degrees of global warming increase the risk of passing through 'tipping points'—thresholds beyond which certain major impacts can no longer be avoided even if temperatures return to their previous state.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For instance, the Greenland ice sheet is already melting, but if global warming reaches levels between 1.7 °C and 2.3 °C, its melting will continue until it fully disappears.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] If the warming is later reduced to 1.5 °C or less, it will still lose a lot more ice than if the warming was never allowed to reach the threshold in the first place.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While the ice sheets would melt over millennia, other tipping points would occur faster and give societies less time to respond.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The collapse of major ocean currents like the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC), and irreversible damage to key ecosystems like the Amazon rainforest and coral reefs can unfold in a matter of decades.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The collapse of the AMOC would be a severe climate catastrophe, resulting in a cooling of the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The long-term effects of climate change on oceans include further ice melt, ocean warming, sea level rise, ocean acidification and ocean deoxygenation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The timescale of long-term impacts are centuries to millennia due to CO2's long atmospheric lifetime.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The result is an estimated total sea level rise of 2.3 metres per degree Celsius (4.2 ft/°F) after 2000 years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Oceanic CO2 uptake is slow enough that ocean acidification will also continue for hundreds to thousands of years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Deep oceans (below 2,000 metres (6,600 ft)) are also already committed to losing over 10% of their dissolved oxygen by the warming which occurred to date.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Further, the West Antarctic ice sheet appears committed to practically irreversible melting, which would increase the sea levels by at least 3.3 m (10 ft 10 in) over approximately 2000 years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Recent warming has driven many terrestrial and freshwater species poleward and towards higher altitudes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For instance, the range of hundreds of North American birds has shifted northward at an average rate of 1.5 km/year over the past 55 years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Higher atmospheric CO2 levels and an extended growing season have resulted in global greening.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] However, heatwaves and drought have reduced ecosystem productivity in some regions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The future balance of these opposing effects is unclear.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] A related phenomenon driven by climate change is woody plant encroachment, affecting up to 500 million hectares globally.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change has contributed to the expansion of drier climate zones, such as the expansion of deserts in the subtropics.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The size and speed of global warming is making abrupt changes in ecosystems more likely.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Overall, it is expected that climate change will result in the extinction of many species.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The oceans have heated more slowly than the land, but plants and animals in the ocean have migrated towards the colder poles faster than species on land.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Just as on land, heat waves in the ocean occur more frequently due to climate change, harming a wide range of organisms such as corals, kelp, and seabirds.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Ocean acidification makes it harder for marine calcifying organisms such as mussels, barnacles and corals to produce shells and skeletons; and heatwaves have bleached coral reefs.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Harmful algal blooms enhanced by climate change and eutrophication lower oxygen levels, disrupt food webs and cause great loss of marine life.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Coastal ecosystems are under particular stress.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Almost half of global wetlands have disappeared due to climate change and other human impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Plants have come under increased stress from damage by insects.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The effects of climate change are impacting humans everywhere in the world.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Impacts can be observed on all continents and ocean regions, with low-latitude, less developed areas facing the greatest risk.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Continued warming has potentially "severe, pervasive and irreversible impacts" for people and ecosystems.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The risks are unevenly distributed, but are generally greater for disadvantaged people in developing and developed countries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Scientists have warned about the irreversible harms it poses.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Extreme weather events affect public health, and food and water security.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Temperature extremes lead to increased illness and death.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change increases the intensity and frequency of extreme weather events.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] It can affect transmission of infectious diseases, such as dengue fever and malaria.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, 14.5 million more deaths are expected due to climate change by 2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] 30% of the global population currently live in areas where extreme heat and humidity are already associated with excess deaths.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] By 2100, 50% to 75% of the global population would live in such areas.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While total crop yields have been increasing in the past 50 years due to agricultural improvements, climate change has already decreased the rate of yield growth.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Fisheries have been negatively affected in multiple regions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While agricultural productivity has been positively affected in some high latitude areas, mid- and low-latitude areas have been negatively affected.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change affects land suitability for many crops, with suitable areas for given crops usually moving to higher latitudes and altitudes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] According to the World Economic Forum, an increase in drought in certain regions could cause 3.2 million deaths from malnutrition by 2050 and stunting in children.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] With 2 °C warming, global livestock headcounts could decline by 7–10% by 2050, as less animal feed will be available.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] If the emissions continue to increase for the rest of century, then over 9 million climate-related deaths would occur annually by 2100.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Economic damages due to climate change may be severe and there is a chance of disastrous consequences.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Severe impacts are expected in South-East Asia and sub-Saharan Africa, where most of the local inhabitants are dependent upon natural and agricultural resources.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Heat stress can prevent outdoor labourers from working.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] If warming reaches 4 °C then labour capacity in those regions could be reduced by 30 to 50%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The World Bank estimates that between 2016 and 2030, climate change could drive over 120 million people into extreme poverty without adaptation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Inequalities based on wealth and social status have worsened due to climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Major difficulties in mitigating, adapting to, and recovering from climate shocks are faced by marginalized people who have less control over resources.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Indigenous people, who are subsistent on their land and ecosystems, will face endangerment to their wellness and lifestyles due to climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] An expert elicitation concluded that the role of climate change in armed conflict has been small compared to factors such as socio-economic inequality and state capabilities.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While women are not inherently more at risk from climate change and shocks, limits on women's resources and discriminatory gender norms constrain their adaptive capacity and resilience.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For example, women's work burdens, including hours worked in agriculture, tend to decline less than men's during climate shocks such as heat stress.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change threatens the sports economy by disrupting seasons, damaging infrastructure and reducing fan engagement, with the most immediate risks seen in football, winter sports and outdoor events.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Low-lying islands and coastal communities are threatened by sea level rise, which makes urban flooding more common.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Sometimes, land is permanently lost to the sea.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This could lead to statelessness for people in island nations, such as the Maldives and Tuvalu.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In some regions, the rise in temperature and humidity may be too severe for humans to adapt to.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] With worst-case climate change, models project that areas almost one-third of humanity live in might become Sahara-like uninhabitable and extremely hot climates.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These factors can drive climate or environmental migration, within and between countries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] More people are expected to be displaced because of sea level rise, extreme weather and conflict from increased competition over natural resources.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change may also increase vulnerability, leading to "trapped populations" who are not able to move due to a lack of resources.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Climate change can be mitigated by reducing the rate at which greenhouse gases are emitted into the atmosphere, and by increasing the rate at which carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] To limit global warming to less than 2 °C global greenhouse gas emissions need to be net-zero by 2070.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This requires far-reaching, systemic changes on an unprecedented scale in energy, land, cities, transport, buildings, and industry.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The United Nations Environment Programme estimates that countries need to triple their pledges under the Paris Agreement within the next decade to limit global warming to 2 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] With pledges made under the Paris Agreement as of 2024, there would be a 66% chance that global warming is kept under 2.8 °C by the end of the century (range: 1.9–3.7 °C, depending on exact implementation and technological progress).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] When only considering current policies, this raises to 3.1 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Globally, limiting warming to 2 °C may result in higher economic benefits than economic costs.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Although there is no single pathway to limit global warming to 2 °C, most scenarios and strategies see a major increase in the use of renewable energy in combination with increased energy efficiency measures to generate the needed greenhouse gas reductions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] To reduce pressures on ecosystems and enhance their carbon sequestration capabilities, changes would also be necessary in agriculture and forestry, such as preventing deforestation and restoring natural ecosystems by reforestation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Other approaches to mitigating climate change have a higher level of risk.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Scenarios that limit global warming to 1.5 °C typically project the large-scale use of carbon dioxide removal methods over the 21st century.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] There are concerns, though, about over-reliance on these technologies, and environmental impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Solar radiation modification (SRM) is a proposal for reducing global warming by reflecting some sunlight away from Earth and back into space.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Because it does not reduce greenhouse gas concentrations, it would not address ocean acidification and is not considered mitigation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] SRM should be considered only as a supplement to mitigation, not a replacement for it, due to risks such as rapid warming if it were abruptly stopped and not restarted.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The most-studied approach is stratospheric aerosol injection.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] SRM could reduce global warming and some of its impacts, though imperfectly.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] It poses environmental risks, such as changes to rainfall patterns, as well as political challenges, such as who would decide whether to use it.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Renewable energy is key to limiting climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For decades, fossil fuels have accounted for roughly 80% of the world's energy use.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The remaining share has been split between nuclear power and renewables (including hydropower, bioenergy, wind and solar power and geothermal energy).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Fossil fuel use is expected to peak in absolute terms prior to 2030 and then to decline, with coal use experiencing the sharpest reductions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Renewables represented 86% of all new electricity generation installed in 2023.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Other forms of clean energy, such as nuclear and hydropower, currently have a larger share of the energy supply.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] However, their future growth forecasts appear limited in comparison.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] While solar panels and onshore wind are now among the cheapest forms of adding new power generation capacity in many locations, green energy policies are needed to achieve a rapid transition from fossil fuels to renewables.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] To achieve carbon neutrality by 2050, renewable energy would become the dominant form of electricity generation, rising to 85% or more by 2050 in some scenarios.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Investment in coal would be eliminated and coal use nearly phased out by 2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Electricity generated from renewable sources would also need to become the main energy source for heating and transport.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Transport can switch away from internal combustion engine vehicles and towards electric vehicles, public transit, and active transport (cycling and walking).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] For shipping and flying, low-carbon fuels would reduce emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Heating could be increasingly decarbonized with technologies like heat pumps.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] There are obstacles to the continued rapid growth of clean energy, including renewables.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Wind and solar produce energy intermittently and with seasonal variability.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Traditionally, hydro dams with reservoirs and fossil fuel power plants have been used when variable energy production is low.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Going forward, battery storage can be expanded, energy demand and supply can be matched, and long-distance transmission can smooth variability of renewable outputs.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Bioenergy is often not carbon-neutral and may have negative consequences for food security.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The growth of nuclear power is constrained by controversy around radioactive waste, nuclear weapon proliferation, and accidents.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Hydropower growth is limited by the fact that the best sites have been developed, and new projects are confronting increased social and environmental concerns.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Low-carbon energy improves human health by minimizing climate change as well as reducing air pollution deaths, which were estimated at 7 million annually in 2016.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Meeting the Paris Agreement goals that limit warming to a 2 °C increase could save about a million of those lives per year by 2050, whereas limiting global warming to 1.5 °C could save millions and simultaneously increase energy security and reduce poverty.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Improving air quality also has economic benefits which may be larger than mitigation costs.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Reducing energy demand is another major aspect of reducing emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] If less energy is needed, there is more flexibility for clean energy development.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] It also makes it easier to manage the electricity grid, and minimizes carbon-intensive infrastructure development.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Major increases in energy efficiency investment will be required to achieve climate goals, comparable to the level of investment in renewable energy.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Several COVID-19 related changes in energy use patterns, energy efficiency investments, and funding have made forecasts for this decade more difficult and uncertain.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Strategies to reduce energy demand vary by sector.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In the transport sector, passengers and freight can switch to more efficient travel modes, such as buses and trains, or use electric vehicles.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Industrial strategies to reduce energy demand include improving heating systems and motors, designing less energy-intensive products, and increasing product lifetimes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In the building sector the focus is on better design of new buildings, and higher levels of energy efficiency in retrofitting.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The use of technologies like heat pumps can also increase building energy efficiency.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Agriculture and forestry face a triple challenge of limiting greenhouse gas emissions, preventing the further conversion of forests to agricultural land, and meeting increases in world food demand.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] A set of actions could reduce agriculture and forestry-based emissions by two-thirds from 2010 levels.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] These include reducing growth in demand for food and other agricultural products, increasing land productivity, protecting and restoring forests, and reducing greenhouse gas emissions from agricultural production.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] On the demand side, a key component of reducing emissions is shifting people towards plant-based diets.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Eliminating the production of livestock for meat and dairy would eliminate about three-quarters of all emissions from agriculture and other land use.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Livestock also occupy 37% of ice-free land area on Earth and consume feed from the 12% of land area used for crops, driving deforestation and land degradation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Steel and cement production are responsible for about 13% of industrial CO2 emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] In these industries, carbon-intensive materials such as coke and lime play an integral role in the production, so that reducing CO2 emissions requires research into alternative chemistries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Where energy production or CO2-intensive heavy industries continue to produce waste CO2, technology can sometimes be used to capture and store most of the gas instead of releasing it to the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] This technology, carbon capture and storage (CCS), could have a critical but limited role in reducing emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] It is relatively expensive and has been deployed only to an extent that removes around 0.1% of annual greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Natural carbon sinks can be enhanced to sequester significantly larger amounts of CO2 beyond naturally occurring levels.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Reforestation and afforestation (planting forests where there were none before) are among the most mature sequestration techniques, although the latter raises food security concerns.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Farmers can promote sequestration of carbon in soils through practices such as use of winter cover crops, reducing the intensity and frequency of tillage, and using compost and manure as soil amendments.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Forest and landscape restoration yields many benefits for the climate, including greenhouse gas emissions sequestration and reduction.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Restoration/recreation of coastal wetlands, prairie plots and seagrass meadows increases the uptake of carbon into organic matter.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] When carbon is sequestered in soils and in organic matter such as trees, there is a risk of the carbon being re-released into the atmosphere later through changes in land use, fire, or other changes in ecosystems.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] The use of bioenergy in conjunction with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) can result in net negative emissions as CO2 is drawn from the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] It remains highly uncertain whether carbon dioxide removal techniques will be able to play a large role in limiting warming to 1.5 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p01] Policy decisions that rely on carbon dioxide removal increase the risk of global warming rising beyond international goals.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Adaptation is "the process of adjustment to current or expected changes in climate and its effects".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Without additional mitigation, adaptation cannot avert the risk of "severe, widespread and irreversible" impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] More severe climate change requires more transformative adaptation, which can be prohibitively expensive.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The capacity and potential for humans to adapt is unevenly distributed across different regions and populations, and developing countries generally have less.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The first two decades of the 21st century saw an increase in adaptive capacity in most low- and middle-income countries with improved access to basic sanitation and electricity, but progress is slow.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Many countries have implemented adaptation policies.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] However, there is a considerable gap between necessary and available finance.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Adaptation to sea level rise consists of avoiding at-risk areas, learning to live with increased flooding, and building flood controls.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] If that fails, managed retreat may be needed.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] There are economic barriers for tackling dangerous heat impact.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Avoiding strenuous work or having air conditioning is not possible for everybody.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In agriculture, adaptation options include a switch to more sustainable diets, diversification, erosion control, and genetic improvements for increased tolerance to a changing climate.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Insurance allows for risk-sharing, but is often difficult to get for people on lower incomes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Education, migration and early warning systems can reduce climate vulnerability.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Planting mangroves or encouraging other coastal vegetation can buffer storms.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Ecosystems adapt to climate change, a process that can be supported by human intervention.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] By increasing connectivity between ecosystems, species can migrate to more favourable climate conditions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Species can also be introduced to areas acquiring a favourable climate.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Protection and restoration of natural and semi-natural areas helps build resilience, making it easier for ecosystems to adapt.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Many of the actions that promote adaptation in ecosystems, also help humans adapt via ecosystem-based adaptation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] For instance, restoration of natural fire regimes makes catastrophic fires less likely, and reduces human exposure.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Giving rivers more space allows for more water storage in the natural system, reducing flood risk.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Restored forest acts as a carbon sink, but planting trees in unsuitable regions can exacerbate climate impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] There are synergies but also trade-offs between adaptation and mitigation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] An example for synergy is increased food productivity, which has large benefits for both adaptation and mitigation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] An example of a trade-off is that increased use of air conditioning allows people to better cope with heat, but increases energy demand.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Another trade-off example is that more compact urban development may reduce emissions from transport and construction, but may also increase the urban heat island effect, exposing people to heat-related health risks.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] ranks countries by greenhouse gas emissions (40% of score), renewable energy (20%), energy use (20%), and climate policy (20%).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Countries that are most vulnerable to climate change have typically been responsible for a small share of global emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] This raises questions about justice and fairness.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Limiting global warming makes it much easier to achieve the UN's Sustainable Development Goals, such as eradicating poverty and reducing inequalities.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The connection is recognized in Sustainable Development Goal 13 which is to "take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The goals on food, clean water and ecosystem protection have synergies with climate mitigation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The geopolitics of climate change is complex.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] It has often been framed as a free-rider problem, in which all countries benefit from mitigation done by other countries, but individual countries would lose from switching to a low-carbon economy themselves.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Sometimes mitigation also has localized benefits though.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] For instance, the benefits of a coal phase-out to public health and local environments exceed the costs in almost all regions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Furthermore, net importers of fossil fuels win economically from switching to clean energy, causing net exporters to face stranded assets: fossil fuels they cannot sell.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] A wide range of policies, regulations, and laws are being used to reduce emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, carbon pricing covers about 20% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Carbon can be priced with carbon taxes and emissions trading systems.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Direct global fossil fuel subsidies reached $319 billion in 2017, and $5.2 trillion when indirect costs such as air pollution are priced in.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Ending these can cause a 28% reduction in global carbon emissions and a 46% reduction in air pollution deaths.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Money saved on fossil subsidies could be used to support the transition to clean energy instead.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] More direct methods to reduce greenhouse gases include vehicle efficiency standards, renewable fuel standards, and air pollution regulations on heavy industry.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Several countries require utilities to increase the share of renewables in power production.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] An Open Coalition on Compliance Carbon Markets with the aim of creating a global cap and trade system was established at COP30 (2025).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] According to some calculations it can increase emissions reduction seven-fold over current policies, deliver $200 billion per year for clean-energy and social programs and even close the gap between current emissions trajectory and the goals of the Paris agreement.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Policy designed through the lens of climate justice tries to address human rights issues and social inequality.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] According to proponents of climate justice, the costs of climate adaptation should be paid by those most responsible for climate change, while the beneficiaries of payments should be those suffering impacts.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] One way this can be addressed in practice is to have wealthy nations pay poorer countries to adapt.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Oxfam found that in 2023 the wealthiest 10% of people were responsible for 50% of global emissions, while the bottom 50% were responsible for just 8%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Production of emissions is another way to look at responsibility: under that approach, the top 21 fossil fuel companies would owe cumulative climate reparations of $5.4 trillion over the period 2025–2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] To achieve a just transition, people working in the fossil fuel sector would also need other jobs, and their communities would need investments.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Nearly all countries in the world are parties to the 1994 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The goal of the UNFCCC is to prevent dangerous human interference with the climate system.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As stated in the convention, this requires that greenhouse gas concentrations are stabilized in the atmosphere at a level where ecosystems can adapt naturally to climate change, food production is not threatened, and economic development can be sustained.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The UNFCCC does not itself restrict emissions but rather provides a framework for protocols that do.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Global emissions have risen since the UNFCCC was signed.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Its yearly conferences are the stage of global negotiations.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The 1997 Kyoto Protocol extended the UNFCCC and included legally binding commitments for most developed countries to limit their emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] During the negotiations, the G77 (representing developing countries) pushed for a mandate requiring developed countries to "[take] the lead" in reducing their emissions, since developed countries contributed most to the accumulation of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Per-capita emissions were also still relatively low in developing countries and developing countries would need to emit more to meet their development needs.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The 2009 Copenhagen Accord has been widely portrayed as disappointing because of its low goals, and was rejected by poorer nations including the G77.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Associated parties aimed to limit the global temperature rise to below 2 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The accord set the goal of sending $100 billion per year to developing countries for mitigation and adaptation by 2020, and proposed the founding of the Green Climate Fund.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As of 2020, only $83.3 billion were delivered.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Only in 2023 the target is expected to be achieved.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In 2015 all UN countries negotiated the Paris Agreement, which aims to keep global warming well below 2.0 °C and contains an aspirational goal of keeping warming under 1.5 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The agreement replaced the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Unlike Kyoto, no binding emission targets were set in the Paris Agreement.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Instead, a set of procedures was made binding.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Countries have to regularly set ever more ambitious goals and reevaluate these goals every five years.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The Paris Agreement restated that developing countries must be financially supported.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As of March 2025, 194 states and the European Union have acceded to or ratified the agreement.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The 1987 Montreal Protocol, an international agreement to phase out production of ozone-depleting gases, has had benefits for climate change mitigation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Several ozone-depleting gases like chlorofluorocarbons are powerful greenhouse gases, so banning their production and usage may have avoided a temperature rise of 0.5 °C–1.0 °C, as well as additional warming by preventing damage to vegetation from ultraviolet radiation.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] It is estimated that the agreement has been more effective at curbing greenhouse gas emissions than the Kyoto Protocol specifically designed to do so.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The most recent amendment to the Montreal Protocol, the 2016 Kigali Amendment, committed to reducing the emissions of hydrofluorocarbons, which served as a replacement for banned ozone-depleting gases and are also potent greenhouse gases.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Should countries comply with the amendment, a warming of 0.3 °C–0.5 °C is estimated to be avoided.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In 2019, the United Kingdom parliament became the first national government to declare a climate emergency.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Other countries and jurisdictions followed suit.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] That same year, the European Parliament declared a "climate and environmental emergency".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The European Commission presented its European Green Deal with the goal of making the EU carbon-neutral by 2050.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains guidelines for the car industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Major countries in Asia have made similar pledges: South Korea and Japan have committed to become carbon-neutral by 2050, and China by 2060.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] While India has strong incentives for renewables, it also plans a significant expansion of coal in the country.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Vietnam is among very few coal-dependent, fast-developing countries that pledged to phase out unabated coal power by the 2040s or as soon as possible thereafter.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Public debate about climate change has been strongly affected by climate change denial and misinformation, which first emerged in the United States and has since spread to other countries, particularly Canada and Australia.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] It originated from fossil fuel companies, industry groups, conservative think tanks, and contrarian scientists.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Like the tobacco industry, the main strategy of these groups has been to manufacture doubt about climate-change related scientific data and results.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] People who hold unwarranted doubt about climate change are sometimes called climate change "skeptics", although "contrarians" or "deniers" are more appropriate terms.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] There are different variants of climate denial: some deny that warming takes place at all, some acknowledge warming but attribute it to natural influences, and some minimize the negative impacts of climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Manufacturing uncertainty about the science later developed into a manufactured controversy: creating the belief that there is significant uncertainty about climate change within the scientific community to delay policy changes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Strategies to promote these ideas include criticism of scientific institutions, and questioning the motives of individual scientists.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] An echo chamber of climate-denying blogs and media has further fomented misunderstanding of climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Climate change came to international public attention in the late 1980s.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Due to media coverage in the early 1990s, people often confused climate change with other environmental issues like ozone depletion.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In popular culture, the climate fiction movie *The Day After Tomorrow* (2004) and the Al Gore documentary *An Inconvenient Truth* (2006) focused on climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Significant regional, gender, age and political differences exist in both public concern for, and understanding of, climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] More highly educated people, and in some countries, women and younger people, were more likely to see climate change as a serious threat.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] College biology textbooks from the 2010s featured less content on climate change compared to those from the preceding decade, with decreasing emphasis on solutions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Partisan gaps also exist in many countries, and countries with high CO2 emissions tend to be less concerned.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Views on causes of climate change vary widely between countries.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Media coverage linked to protests has had impacts on public sentiment as well as on which aspects of climate change are focused upon.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Higher levels of worry are associated with stronger public support for policies that address climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Concern has increased over time, and in 2021 a majority of citizens in 30 countries expressed a high level of worry about climate change, or view it as a global emergency.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] A 2024 survey across 125 countries found that 89% of the global population demanded intensified political action, but systematically underestimated other peoples' willingness to act.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Climate protests demand that political leaders take action to prevent climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] They can take the form of public demonstrations, fossil fuel divestment, lawsuits and other activities.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Prominent demonstrations include the School Strike for Climate.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In this initiative, young people across the globe have been protesting since 2018 by skipping school on Fridays, inspired by Swedish activist and then-teenager Greta Thunberg.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Mass civil disobedience actions by groups like Extinction Rebellion have protested by disrupting roads and public transport.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Litigation is increasingly used as a tool to strengthen climate action from public institutions and companies.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Activists also initiate lawsuits which target governments and demand that they take ambitious action or enforce existing laws on climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Lawsuits against fossil-fuel companies generally seek compensation for loss and damage.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] On 23 July 2025, the UN's International Court of Justice issued its advisory opinion, saying explicitly that states must act to stop climate change, and if they fail to accomplish that duty, other states can sue them.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] This obligation includes implementing their commitments in international agreements they are parties to, such as the 2015 Paris Climate Accord.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Scientists in the 19th century such as Alexander von Humboldt began to foresee the effects of climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In the 1820s, Joseph Fourier proposed the greenhouse effect to explain why Earth's temperature was higher than the Sun's energy alone could explain.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Earth's atmosphere is transparent to sunlight, so sunlight reaches the surface where it is converted to heat.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] However, the atmosphere is not transparent to heat radiating from the surface, and captures some of that heat, which in turn warms the planet.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In 1856 Eunice Newton Foote demonstrated that the warming effect of the Sun is greater for air with water vapour than for dry air, and that the effect is even greater with carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In "Circumstances Affecting the Heat of the Sun's Rays" she concluded that "[a]n atmosphere of that gas would give to our earth a high temperature".
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Starting in 1859, John Tyndall established that nitrogen and oxygen—together totalling 99% of dry air—are transparent to radiated heat.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] However, water vapour and gases such as methane and carbon dioxide absorb radiated heat and re-radiate that heat into the atmosphere.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Tyndall proposed that changes in the concentrations of these gases may have caused climatic changes in the past, including ice ages.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Svante Arrhenius noted that water vapour in air continuously varied, but the CO2 concentration in air was influenced by long-term geological processes.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Warming from increased CO2 levels would increase the amount of water vapour, amplifying warming in a positive feedback loop.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In 1896, he published the first climate model of its kind, projecting that halving CO2 levels could have produced a drop in temperature initiating an ice age.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Arrhenius calculated the temperature increase expected from doubling CO2 to be around 5–6 °C.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Other scientists were initially sceptical and believed that the greenhouse effect was saturated so that adding more CO2 would make no difference, and that the climate would be self-regulating.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Beginning in 1938, Guy Stewart Callendar published evidence that climate was warming and CO2 levels were rising, but his calculations met the same objections.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] In the 1950s, Gilbert Plass created a detailed computer model that included different atmospheric layers and the infrared spectrum.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] This model predicted that increasing CO2 levels would cause warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Around the same time, Hans Suess found evidence that CO2 levels had been rising, and Roger Revelle showed that the oceans would not absorb the increase.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The two scientists subsequently helped Charles Keeling to begin a record of continued increase—the "Keeling Curve"—which was part of continued scientific investigation through the 1960s into possible human causation of global warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Studies such as the National Research Council's 1979 Charney Report supported the accuracy of climate models that forecast significant warming.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Human causation of observed global warming and dangers of unmitigated warming were publicly presented in James Hansen's 1988 testimony before a US Senate committee.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), set up in 1988 to provide formal advice to the world's governments, spurred interdisciplinary research.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As part of the IPCC reports, scientists assess the scientific discussion that takes place in peer-reviewed journal articles.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] There is a nearly unanimous scientific consensus that the climate is warming and that this is caused by human activities.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] No scientific body of national or international standing disagrees with this view.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] As of 2019, agreement in recent literature reached over 99%.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] The 2021 IPCC Assessment Report stated that it is "unequivocal" that climate change is caused by humans.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Consensus has further developed that action should be taken to protect people against the impacts of climate change.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] National science academies have called on world leaders to cut global emissions.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Extreme event attribution (EEA), also known as attribution science, was developed in the early decades of the 21st century.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] EEA uses climate models to identify and quantify the role that human-caused climate change plays in the frequency, intensity, duration, and impacts of specific individual extreme weather events.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Greater computing power in the 2000s and conceptual breakthroughs in the early to mid 2010s enabled attribution science to detect the effects of climate change on some events with high confidence.
[src:climate-change/climate-change-p02] Scientists use attribution methods and climate simulations that have already been peer reviewed, allowing "rapid attribution studies" to be published within a "news cycle" time frame after weather events.
